<FIRST>r i PM-NATOAdviser     07-04 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO Adviser,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>US NATO Official Ends Career, Seeing Enormous Changes in Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Legere has watched NATO develop
from a fledgling alliance dominated by the United States into one
that reflects Western Europe's increasing preoccupation with its own
interests and destiny.
   Legere, 70, is ending a career that took him to Normandy in World
War II, the White House during the Cuban missile crisis and to
Europe as the Defense Department's top civilian outside Washington.
   His last job, defense adviser to the U.S. Mission to NATO since
1974, has given him a close look at his country's European allies.
   ``I really have the feeling of ... a time of great change,''
Legere said in a recent interview at North Atlantic Treaty
Organization headquarters in Brussels. ``It will be fascinating to
watch.''
   He is retiring to North Carolina after 15 years of advising
American defense secretaries on sensitive security issues.
Reflecting on his experiences, he said:
   ``The Europeans are thinking differently. The people coming to
power now ... didn't experience World War II'' and are less reliant
on the United States.
   ``When we were the real leaders of the alliance, damn near
anything we said went,'' Legere said. ``They were good at
calibrating how serious the United States was about something.''
   When a new president was elected, Europeans wondered, ``What was
Jimmy Carter going to do ... what was this cowboy Reagan going to be
like,'' he said, but there was less of that in May during President
Bush's first summit of the 16-nation alliance.
   ``They don't feel as dependent on where an administration is
going to go,'' he said. ``They are beginning to feel more European
about all this.''
   Much of Western Europe's new closeness stems from the plan of the
12-nation European Economic Community to form a single market in
late 1992, ending the many trade barriers that now exist.
   ``The idea of Europe is very much on the move,'' Legere said.
   Relations with the Soviet Union, once eyed suspiciously in
Western Europe, also have changed since Mikhail S. Gorbachev gained
control of the Kremlin in 1985.
   ``You've got people who don't consider the Soviet Union the evil
empire or evil incarnate,'' Legere said, but recommended caution in
case Gorbachev doesn't last.
   Even with reduced tension in Europe, Legere feels there is room
for the defensive alliance linking the United States and Canada with
their European allies.
   ``The question is what kind of a place and doing what,'' he said.
``My own view is that NATO will continue to play a vital role in
military defense and defense questions. It's just the only place
that it can be done.''
   He does not believe Europe will become strong enough to replace
the United States as a global power.
   ``We are still the superpower,'' he said. ``Even an ideally and
perfectly united Europe, which won't happen, would not be in the
league with us and the Soviet Union.''
   Legere spiced his remembrances with tales of naive American
politicians crossing the Atlantic to offer their views on defense
matters.
   Years ago, he said, one such told Soviet arms negotiators Moscow
and Washington avoid complicated bargaining and just pull out a
large number of forces from Europe.
   ``You don't say these kinds of things in that sort of company and
I can remember the Russians being really nonplussed by it,'' Legere
said.
   He was born on Jan. 2, 1919, in Fitchburg, Mass., attended West
Point at age 17 and retired from the Army as a colonel in 1966.
   On D-Day, June 6, 1944, Legere was wounded after parachuting
behind Utah Beach in France, which interfered with his plans. He was
carrying a dress uniform and two bottles of scotch, because ``I was
convinced we were going to be in Paris in about two weeks and I
didn't want to be caught short.''
   His career included several stints as a White House adviser.
   In October 1962, it was his responsibility to awaken President
John F. Kennedy with important developments. A long, rambling cable
arrived from Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev during the night.
   ``I read that thing a dozen times all night long, and I did
nothing,'' Legere said. ``I'll never know whether I did the right
thing or not.''
   Next day, the National Security Council began debating what to
do, and was still at it in the evening.
   ``This could be the last night of my life, and a lot of other
people's,'' Legere said. He added, with a laugh, that he went to a
nearby hotel ``and got smashed.''
</TEXT>
