<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Japan-Phones     07-04 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Japan-Phones,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Information Society to Bring 8-Digit Phone Numbers to Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Move over, Paris. Tokyo will join you in the ranks
of cities with eight-digit phone numbers.
   Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. said Tuesday that the change
from seven-digit phone numbers in Tokyo will take place Jan. 1,
1991. Subscribers will add a 3 at the beginning of their seven-digit
numbers.
   The national telephone utility said a shortage of exchange
numbers began showing up in 1981 as demand increased for facsimile
and microcomputer communications on top of demand for regular
telephone lines.
   Some eight-digit phone numbers were given to pocket pagers in
1987, and in 1988 some new subscribers for regular phones received
eight-digit numbers, NTT said, but by early 1991 the shortage will
be acute.
   Unlike in France, which has had eight-digit local phone numbers
throughout the country for several years, the change in Japan will
affect only phone numbers in Tokyo, a city of 12 million people.
</TEXT>
