<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 2358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FiresRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0667 07-04 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0667,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Try to Pick up the Pieces After Devastating Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Turnbull Canyon fire contained,
new fire in San Bernardino National Forest; picks up 4th graf, `Elsewhere,
fire ...;' SUBS 22nd graf, `Firefighters also ...,' to UPDATE Utah fire
acerage.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACIENDA HEIGHTS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters racing rising
temperatures Tuesday contained a blaze that leveled 13 homes,
damaged eight others, charred 1,500 acres of brush and did $4.3
million damage in an exclusive hillside neighborhood.
   ``We should get control of it pretty soon,'' Joe Silva of the Los
Angeles County Fire Department said after the fire was declared
contained at 5:20 p.m.
   Cool, humid night air slowed the blaze after it ravaged the
neighborhood Monday, and about half of the roughly 1,000
firefighters were allowed to go home, Silva said.
   But temperatures soared as high as 109 degrees and winds were up
to 12 mph.
   And, in the San Bernardino National Forest, a new blaze burned
150 acres in Santa Ana Canyon about 70 miles east of Los Angeles.
   About 200 firefighters were dispatched, and six fire-retardant
dropping planes and three helicopters attacked the blaze, said
Bureau of Land Management dispatcher Allyn Harrington.
   Elsewhere, fire crews battled forest and brush fires in mostly
remote areas of Colorado, Utah, Wyoming and New Mexico, where a
large fire threatened an endangered species of trout.
   Police allowed residents back into the Turnbull Canyon area, 20
miles east of downtown Los Angeles, early Tuesday to survey the
damage in the neighborhood, where homes are valued at $300,000 to
more than $1 million.
   ``We realize how important it was for people to go back in and
check. Some were going crazy,'' said Capt. Garry Oversby.
   Thirteen homes were destroyed and eight sustained major damage,
Silva said. Damage to property and land was estimated at at least $4
million.
   Four people were arrested for looting late Monday, Silva said.
``I cannot believe they would want to take more from people who
already have lost almost everything,'' he said.
   Don Younger said he had been visiting friends Monday when he saw
a plume of black smoke from his neighborhood. When he tried to drive
home fire officials would not allow him through, so he drove to a
hill where he could watch.
   ``I saw the firefighters down on their bellies saving my home. I
wish I could hug them all,'' he said. The blaze destroyed a small
structure behind his home containing about $20,000 worth of amateur
radio equipment.
   Younger said his house, which he valued at $250,000, sustained
some $12,000 in fire damage in 1968.
   Two houses down, Jim Ahrens swept up ashes and charred wood
inside an addition to his home that was to have been an exercise
room. He also lost a bathroom. ``It could have been a lot worse,''
he said.
   About 300 evacuees registered at a shelter at a high school,
mostly to let relatives know they were safe, then spent the night
with friends or family, said Robert Crompton, disaster services
chairman of the American Red Cross.
   The fire was believed to have been caused by people, fire
Inspector John Lenihan said. It began in a brushy area and spread
quickly to homes.
   ``There was no reason for anyone to have been there,'' he said of
the area where the fire started.
   In southwestern New Mexico, a wind-driven fire had charred about
5,000 acres near Diamond Peak in the Gila National Forest. Forest
Service spokesman Ken Palmrose said crews had to use hand tools on
the fire line in steep terrain straddling the Continental Divide at
9,000 feet.
   Nearly 850 people, six air tankers and seven helicopters fought
the fire, which was started by lightning Friday and spread by 30 mph
wind.
   The fire threatened the Gila trout, which are listed as an
endangered species, a U.S. Forest Service spokesman said
   ``Some people might not understand how fish can be threatened by
fire, but these are creeks with very little water,'' said Ken
Palmrose. ``The fish might be in little pools or in an area with
very little stream flow.''
   Biologists planned to use nets to catch as many Gila trout as
possible and bring them to a hatchery.
   Several fires in Colorado had been contained or controlled, but
the Box Canyon fire, south of Dinosaur National Monument, grew to
1,800 acres Tuesday and entered the Skull Creek Wilderness Study
Area.
   Firefighters also battled extreme heat and low humidity to
suppress fires in eastern and southern Utah, while a new blaze
charred more than 1,000 acres in the Uintah Basin, forcing
evacuation of all campgrounds in the area.
   In Wyoming, a fire that scorched 400 acres in the Bridger-Teton
National Forest was expected to burn up to 1,000 acres before crews
could extinguish it, said U.S. Forest Service spokesman Fred
Kingwill.
   The fire is the first significant blaze in the forest so far this
year, he said.
</TEXT>
