<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Negroponte     07-04 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Negroponte,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negroponte Presents Credentials in Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New U.S. Ambassador John D. Negroponte says
there is no basis to fears expressed in Mexico that his appointment
is a sign of intentions by Washington to intervene in Mexico's
internal affairs.
   ``Those fears are completely without foundation,'' Negroponte
said Monday, replying to a question from a Mexican journalist after
presenting his credentials to President Carlos Salinas de Gortari at
the National Palace.
   Many Mexican commentators speculated on the meaning of
Negroponte's appointment, noting that he was ambassador to Honduras
during the buildup of the Nicaraguan Contra rebel movement there.
   Because of a history of conflicts starting with the Mexican War
in 1846, Mexicans are highly sensitive to any hint of U.S.
interventionism.
   ``It is not my intention to bring about intervention of any
sort,'' Negroponte said. ``I want to promote good relations between
the two nations.''
   Speaking in Spanish, Negroponte noted in a statement that he was
a 28-year career diplomat and said there was no ``relationship more
important than the relationship between Mexico and the United
States.''
   He said he was anxious to ``build on the spirit of Houston,''
where Salinas and President Bush met last November, before either
had taken office.
   In a brief question and answer session after the ceremony,
Negroponte praised the Salinas administration's effort to fight drug
trafficking.
   ``The United States is very satisfied with the collaboration that
has developed between our two governments,'' Negroponte said.
   Asked what he thought of Mexico's policies in Central America,
Negroponte said the main issues between the two nations are
bilateral.
   ``Naturally our governments will sometimes exchange points of
view on other themes, but always on the basis of mutual respect,''
Negroponte said, using a phrase _ ``mutual respect'' _ that is a
keynote for politicians here when they discuss relations with the
United States.
   Under the administration of President Miguel de la Madrid, Mexico
opposed U.S. policy in Central America, particularly its support of
the Contra rebels who fought the leftist Sandinista government in
Nicaragua.
   But in May, when tensions rose between the United States and the
Panama over what Washington called a fraudulent election and over
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's role in the government, Mexico
temporarily withdrew its envoy to Panama _ an almost unprecedented
display of support for a U.S. position.
   Negroponte's role in the Contra buildup figured during the
confirmation process in the U.S. Senate following his nomination by
Bush, but he was confirmed easily.
   The 50-year-old diplomat served as ambassador to Honduras from
1981 to 1985, then served in the White House as part of the national
security staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
