<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion-Impact     07-04 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Impact,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Encourages States to Restrict Abortion, Activists Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Johnsen with an `e' in 3rd graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposed restrictions on abortion are waiting
in the wings in many states now that the Supreme Court has approved
such limits, say activists on both sides of the issue.
   Monday's decision did not impose immediate restrictions in any
state other than Missouri, the state affected by the case.
   But Dawn Johnsen, legal counsel of the National Abortion Rights
Action League, said over 250 abortion-related bills were introduced
in various states in 1988 and 1989.
   ``All but a handful of states had some activity,'' she said. ``I
expect that the court's decision will encourage state legislatures
to introduce numerous restrictions on abortions.''
   Douglas Johnson, legislative director of the National Right to
Life Committee, said he thought the quickest impact may come from
courts that have enjoined laws in various states.
   ``Now those lower courts will review some of those injunctions,''
he said.
   He called the decision ``an invitation by the court to the states
to begin to restore protection to unborn children.'' And, Johnson
added, ``I'm sure that a number of legislatures will accept the
invitation.''
   Most state legislatures are not in session at this time of year,
he noted, and there is time to analyze the decision and enact new
laws.
   ``The telephones are ringing off the hook,'' said Sue Roselle,
executive director of Women's Health Services Inc. of Pittsburgh, a
non-profit clinic that performs about 7,000 abortions per year.
   ``Women are saying, `I want my abortion now before they change
the law,''' she said.
   Eve Paul, vice president for legal affairs for Planned Parenthood
Federation of America, said the decision ``is just opening it up for
endless battles in the legislatures and the courts.
   ``We expect many states to enact laws that restrict abortion
rights in a variety of ways,'' she said. ``We expect to be in court
challenging many of those. I think they will start off with
provisions that are similar to the Missouri law.''
   Ms. Paul said, too, that women's rights groups will indicate to
legislators that abortion will be a key election issue next year.
   ``People, women in particular, are not very conscious of the role
that state legislatures played in their lives,'' she said. ``This
opens the way for a lot more public concern as to who is my state
legislator and what is his position on abortion.''
   In the past decade, about 1.5 million legal abortions have been
performed each year.
   In Louisiana, Attorney General William Guste said the decision
might warrant reconsideration of a law, declared unconstitutional in
1982, that requires ultrasound testing of a fetus prior to any
abortion. But he declined to speculate what the legislature might do.
   Some state legislators are predicting there won't be much action
in their states as a result of the rulings.
   ``I would anticipate a lot of sound and fury but no substantive
action by the legislature next year,'' said Washington State House
Speaker Joe King. ``After all, Washington voters approved of
abortion and the spending of state money to pay for abortion.''
   And in New York state, with the most liberal laws in the country,
chances are thought slim that the laws will be tightened. Women's
groups will be mobilized to hold the line, said Shirley Gordon,
executive director of Family Planning Advocates of New York State.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
