<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion-Quotes     07-04 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Quotes,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Officials, Activists Say About Abortion Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from statements and
interviews of government officials and activists on both sides of
the abortion issue reacting to the Supreme Court decision on
abortion.
   President Bush: ``... the court appears to have begun to restore
to the people the ability to protect the unborn ... We continue to
believe that Roe vs. Wade was incorrectly decided and should be
reversed.''
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh: ``... those of us opposed to
abortion on demand can take heart that a majority of the justices
have seen fit to give the states greater leeway in establishing
appropriate limitations on abortion.''
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo.: ``What today did was made women
wards of the state. We're the only ones in the whole Western
civilized world with this ruling.''
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio: ``The decision should serve as a
rallying cry to women everywhere to fight these back door attempts
to limit their right to privacy.''
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.: ``By cutting back on Roe vs. Wade,
the court has seriously undermined the Constitution's protection of
women in our society.''
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.: The ruling is ``the first big step
toward overturning Roe vs. Wade and another step toward the end of
the killing of prenatal infants.''
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah: ``I remain hopeful the court will soon
overturn Roe outright.''
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif.: ``It won't stop abortions. It will
only make many unsafe abortions likely.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.: ``Overwhelmingly, poor women
unable to travel from state to state will be the losers _ and the
casualties of self-induced and back-alley abortions.''
   Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J.: The ruling ``is a significant
victory for unborn children and will likely result in the saving of
many children who otherwise would have been aborted.''
   Faye Wattleton, president of Planned Parenthood Federation of
America: ``Now a woman's access to abortion may become hostage to
geography, as states enact a patchwork of laws and regulations aimed
at blocking abortion.''
   John Willke, president of National Right to Life Committee: The
ruling ``begins the process of restoring a fundamental right of the
American people _ the right to protect human life.''
   Kate Michelman, executive director of National Abortion Rights
Action League: ``Women's lives hang by a thread, and the justices
this morning handed politicians a pair of scissors.''
   National Abortion Federation: ``Whether a woman can exercise her
constitutional right to abortion will increasingly depend on where
she lives, how much money she has and how far she is able to
travel.''
   Norma McCorvey, who as ``Jane Roe'' brought the lawsuit that led
to the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision: ``It saddens my heart very deeply
to know that poor women are once again going to be out there going
to backstreet abortions and possibly be mutilated and not have the
right to choose.''
   Randall Terry, national director of Operation Rescue: ``It's a
faltering step under which children will continue to be murdered,
but this decision indicates that Roe's days are numbered.''
   National Conference of Catholic Bishops, by its president,
Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis: ``The court's decision is a
victory for life. And the bggest winners today are the tiniest
people of all _ children within the womb.''
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women:
``This is war against women.''
   Judith Widdecombe, founder of Reproductive Health Services, the
Missouri clinic involved in the lawsuit that led to Monday's
decision: ``This is the beginning of a war. It will become our
Vietnam of the 1990s.'''
   Gwendolyn Calvert Baker, national executive director of the YWCA
of the U.S.A.: ``For all women, this decision threatens our civil
liberties and our economic security, our privacy and our health.''
   Janet Benshoop of the American Civil Liberties Union: ``Today's
decision strikes a blow to all Americans who look to the
Constitution and the Supreme Court to safeguard their privacy and
freedom.''
   Committee for Family America: ``Clearly Roe is in its death
throes. ... The end to `constitutional' abortion is in sight.''
</TEXT>
