<FIRST>r w PM-ChineseFireworks     07-04 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Fireworks,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chances Are That July 4 Firecracker Was Made in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the fireworks being set off to
celebrate American freedom this week were shipped from China before
that country's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, a
fireworks expert says.
   The Chinese have targeted the U.S. fireworks market since
relations improved during the Nixon administration and now dominate
the market, said John A. Conkling, a Maryland chemist who heads the
American Pyrotechnics Association.
   Conkling, who operates a seasonal ``Fireworks Hotline'' in
Washington, said shipments from China had either arrived or were
aboard vessels by the time the disturbances began that led to last
month's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators. Hundreds,
perhaps thousands, of people were killed.
   ``I think the fact that for the past 15 years we've celebrated
Independence Day with fireworks coming from a communist country
means there has been an irony quite a while,'' he said. ``It is
heightened by the incidents this year.''
   Most fireworks used by Americans come from overseas, more than
half from China, he said, adding that the question concerning
possible trade sanctions would be, ``Whom do you punish?''
   In 1987, the latest year for which he had full statistics, 50
million pounds of fireworks came to the United States directly from
China and more than 10 million pounds came from China by way of Hong
Kong distributors. That left just 6 million pounds exported to the
United States by the rest of the world, including such former
fireworks-making giants as Taiwan and Macao.
   Most of the fireworks are of the backyard variety _ firecrackers,
Roman candles, skyrockets _ and not the kind seen at public displays.
   Commerce Department figures show Chinese shipments of
``explosives and pyrotechnics'' have risen steadily since 1983, when
they were valued at $33.4 million, to $51.2 million in 1987.
   The Chinese, who made ``fire lances'' with a mixture of
saltpeter, sulfur and charcoal as early as the 12th century, now
tailor their products for Americans.
   For instance, the Chinese began making sparklers because
Americans wanted them.
   Many of the fireworks on display at roadside stands still have
distinct oriental imagery: pagodas, blossoms and butterflies.
   A $13 package put together by a New Jersey company is called the
``Miss Liberty'' assortment. A few of the pieces in it are Chinese,
including one with unintended timeliness: A tiny Chinese-made paper
tank moves on the ground and ``emits flaming pellets.''
   For years, controversy over the Chinese imports has involved
safety rather than questions of politics or human rights in China.
   Last year, the Consumer Product Safety Commission and the Customs
Service seized so many Chinese fireworks for bad labels, short fuses
or gunpowder overloads that the industry had to shut down for a time.
   Conkling was among a group of American experts who toured the
Chinese fireworks provinces last year to work with the makers on
safety standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890704-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 0042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CapitalFourth     07-04 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Fourth,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's Capital Plans Festive Fourth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chinese Fireworks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as a half-million people were expected
to celebrate Independence Day in the nation's capital today with a
full day of activities, beginning with a parade and ending with
fireworks.
   Stars scheduled for Fourth of July performances in Washington
included James Galway, Henry Mancini, Pearl Bailey, Peter Nero and
Gary Morris.
   Earle Kittleman, spokesman for the National Park Service, said
authorities were preparing for anywhere from 300,000 to 500,000
people to converge on the National Mall and nearby viewing points,
with several concerts leading up to the fireworks near the
Washington Monument.
   The forecast was for partly cloudy skies with scattered showers
and highs in the low to mid-80s.
   The day's major events were to begin with a parade along
Constitution Avenue before noon.
   Among the scheduled concerts was the National Symphony Orchestra,
which was to perform an evening concert on the west front of the
Capitol narrated by actor E.G. Marshall.
   In addition, singer Gary Morris was joining the Navy Band in a
performance at the Sylvan Theater, adjacent to the Washington
Monument, and the Air Force Band was performing on the steps of the
National Air and Space Museum.
   The city also had a day-long jazz festival set for Freedom Plaza
on Pennsylvania Avenue, two blocks from the White House.
</TEXT>
