<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 0104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Peru     07-04 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Novelist Vargas Llosa Resumes Bid For Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Mario Vargas Llosa has stepped back
into the race for president after putting to rest internal squabbles
within his center-right coalition.
   The acclaimed 53-year-old writer reversed himself Monday after
shocking Peru's political circles by withdrawing his candidacy June
21 and leaving for Europe.
   At the time, he criticized the ``mediocre and petty'' motives of
some members of the coalition that nominated him. He said they were
putting their own parochial interests above those of the nation.
   Peru is beset by economic chaos and a growing leftist insurgency.
   Public opinion polls show Vargas Llosa with 44 percent of voter
support, more than double the figure for his principal rival,
Alfonso Barrantes, a Marxist and former mayor of Lima.
   Speaking at a news conference broadcast from Madrid, Spain,
Vargas Llosa said Monday that the Democratic Front, the center-right
coalition that nominated him on June 4, had resolved its internal
dispute over municipal elections.
   Analysts said Vargas Llosa's handling of the issue strengthened
his leadership role within the alliance and demonstrated his
political skill and determination to be more than a figurehead for
old-line leaders.
   The two major coalition parties, the Popular Action Party of
former President Fernando Belaunde Terry and the Popular Christian
Party, had threatened to run their own candidates in November
municipal elections.
   Last week, the parties agreed to Vargas Llosa's demand that the
coalition, rather than individual parties, would put forward
candidates. He said this was necessary to keep the Democratic Front
united for next year's presidential election.
   In his letter of resignation, he said that even if the coalition
were to win the presidency, the disputes would leave the new
government too weak to confront the leftist insurgency or resolve
Peru's economic ills.
   The government's nine-year struggle against Maoist Shining Path
guerrillas has claimed more than 15,000 lives. Meanwhile, inflation
has reached an annual rate of nearly 6,000 percent.
   In his Monday news conference broadcast on Peruvian TV and radio,
Vargas Llosa said ``the differences'' that led him to resign no
longer existed.
   He said the parties ``have reached an agreement that seems very
reasonable to me and I think also to most of the public.''
   Vargas Llosa said he planned to return to Lima this week to
resume his campaign.
   The election is planned for March, but an exact date has not been
set. The winner is to take office on July 28.
   For months, opponents of Vargas Llosa have hinted that the writer
did not have the political strength for a presidential campaign. But
analysts said Monday that his firmness on municipal elections showed
he is far tougher than even his coalition allies realized.
   Vargas Llosa was catapulted into the political arena after
organizing a huge demonstration against populist President Alan
Garcia's plan to nationalize banks. He said the takeover attempt
represented a ``totalitarian'' threat to the Peruvian economy.
   He found himself transformed overnight into a new political
leader, and conservatives saw in him a man who could return them to
power.
</TEXT>
