<DOCNO> AP890704-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 0107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ArtHouse Bjt   07-04 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Art House, Bjt,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artists Turn Home Into Work of Art</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELLENSBURG, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It began with a pair of pink flamingos.
A decade later Dick and Jane's Spot has become a work of art.
   Festooned with 1,600 bicycle reflectors, 20,000 bottle caps and a
6-foot hand that once belonged to a fortune teller, the home of
artists Dick Elliott and Jane Orleman is their largest art work.
   ``Art over the years was a very serious thing and we feel this is
a more fun point of view,'' said Jane, 47. ``We don't try to
represent the angst of the world. We try to alleviate it.''
   Located on a quiet street in this university town of 11,000
residents, Dick and Jane's Spot, which doubles as their residence,
has been surprising and delighting passersby since 1979.
   A combination roadside attraction and full-size playhouse, the
Spot is an ever-changing work, with sunlight reflecting different
colors from each reflector, and more than 100 silver bicycle wheels
whirling in the wind. The bottle caps rust and the garden changes
through the seasons.
   The couple recently received a $2,500 grant from Art Matters
Inc., a New York City foundation, to install lights in the yard, so
darkness can no longer obscure the sights.
   They bought the 100-year-old frame house for $18,000 when it was
a decrepit wreck in 1978, and shortly after received a pair of pink
flamingos from Jane's mother.
   They soon began adding things. Over the years, about 30 artists
have contributed carvings, sculpture and other pieces. The 100
separate works include carved heads, a sculpture using a huge fish
net, and a brick fountain in the shape of a heart known as the Heart
of Washington. That is a pun on Ellensburg's location in the center
of the state.
   ``It's sort of turning into a private museum for folk art,'' said
Dick, 43. ``We've become a humane society for lost art.''
   The most popular work is a statue of a man with a camera for a
face and flashcubes for eyeballs, Dick said.
   ``It's a camera-faced tourist,'' he said. ``People really like
that one.''
   There is a guest book outside the fence with a sign saying ``What
is this place?'' above it.
   That's the most frequently heard question, Dick said.
   Now included on tour bus stops, The Spot is surrounded by a
wooden fence. The major works are in the front and back yards and
can be viewed from the sidewalk.
   ``We are not open to the public,'' Dick said. ``We don't want
people coming into the yard.''
   The couple met when both were art students at Central Washington
University in Ellensburg.
   When they aren't replacing the bicycle reflectors or fixing the
rotating wheels, they operate the Spot Janitorial Co., which cleans
businesses in the area.
   They work part-time running the business, with the rest of the
time devoted to art.
   Dick makes ``paintings'' using thousands of small reflectors.
   He has a show opening at the Deson-Saunders gallery in Chicago,
another opening soon at the Richard Gasperi gallery in New Orleans,
and has had shows in the Seattle area.
   One of his paintings requiring 25,000 reflectors will be
installed at the University of Washington this fall, and they just
received a fellowship from the Bellevue Art Museum.
   ``I'm the only person I know of using reflectors as a painting
medium,'' Dick said, adding he had to search for years before
finding a factory to produce the reflectors.
   Jane also is a painter, although ``generally with actual paint.''
   She also has created several of the sculptures in the yard.
   The Orlemans, married 18 years, have no intention of selling the
house.
   ``It's home,'' Jane said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890704-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Missouri     07-04 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Missouri,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missouri Law Won't Have Much Impact on Availability of Abortions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion-Laws, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri's anti-abortion law won't
have a dramatic impact on the availability of abortions in the
state. But both sides say the Supreme Court's decision upholding the
law has far-reaching potential.
   ``I think it will not only save the unborn child, but also save
the women who were being exploited. That's been the bottom line
goal,'' said Lou DeFeo of the Missouri Catholic Conference, who
helped write the 1986 Missouri law.
   But DeFeo acknowledged, ``If a woman really wants an abortion in
Missouri, she can get it.''
   On Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld key provisions of the
Missouri law that prohibits public hospitals from performing
abortions and bans the use of tax dollars for counseling or
encouraging women about abortion. It also requires doctors to test
for the viability of a fetus after 20 weeks.
   ``The immediate impact will not be all that substantial,'' said
state Attorney General William Webster, who argued the case before
the court.
   He noted that most abortions in Missouri are performed in private
clinics, not public ones affected by the ruling.
   State health officials said that of the 17,382 abortions
performed in Missouri last year, only 90 were performed in public
hospitals.
   ``I think the real significance is not short term, but long
term,'' Webster said, predicting that states will pass a ``second
generation'' of laws that regulate abortions.
   Supporters of abortion rights called the ruling a devastating
setback that will prompt further efforts to outlaw abortions. They
said the impact on Missouri will fall hardest on poor women.
   Mary Bryant, a Planned Parenthood lobbyist who fought the law,
said she expected an ``avalanche'' of restrictive legislation
introduced in Missouri and other states.
   Bryant said the law's requirement for viability testing is cruel
because most women who have abortions after the first trimester are
poor and young. During the first few months, some don't know what is
happening to them, she said.
   But DeFeo said the Missouri law will stop second trimester
abortions for women and by doctors who had been ``hedging on the
truth and performing an abortion on a viable child as if it weren't
a viable child.''
   Gov. John Ashcroft, a staunch anti-abortionist, said he would
appoint a task force to study how the state could further restrict
abortions.
   Asked if he would appoint any pro-choice advocates, Ashcroft
said, ``It would not be appropriate to have groups that recommend
abortion on the panel.''
   Webster said two public hospitals will have to stop performing
abortions _ Truman Medical Center in Kansas City and the University
of Missouri Hospital and Clinics in Columbia.
   Dr. James Mongan, executive director of the 360-bed Truman
Medical Center, said the hospital will stop performing abortions,
which are paid for by the patient. Abortions in Missouri have not
been financed with public money since the mid-1970s.
   Officials at University of Missouri said their doctors also will
stop performing abortions.
   The executive director of Reproductive Heath Services, the
private St. Louis clinic that challenged the law, said her clinic
will continue to provide ``all choices to women, regardless of their
ability to pay.''
   ``This is a tragedy ... that will affect mostly low-income
women,'' said B.J. Isaacson-Jones. ``I am filled with grief, rage
and bitter disappointment.''
   The cost of abortions for low-income women at the private clinic
is determined on a sliding scale. The standard fee for
first-trimester abortions is $260.
   Judith Widdicombe, founder of the clinic, called the decision an
outrage.
   ``There's a movement in this country that will not tolerate this.
It will become our Vietnam of the 1990s,'' she said.
   ``Their goal is no abortions,'' Widdicombe said. ``Next will come
birth control.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
