<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     07-04 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Bars Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama has been declared ineligible for more
loans from the International Monetary Fund because it has fallen
behind on repayments of $163 million borrowed earlier.
   Panama's total debt is over $5 billion. Panama is one of 151
member governments in the fund.
   The ban was decided Monday by the 22 members of the Executive
Board, who meet behind closed doors. They usually act by consensus.
   In the past two years, U.S. financial sanctions against Manuel
Antonio Noriega have failed to dislodge him as Panama's leader.
Noriega has been indicted on U.S. drug trafficking charges.
   Panama is the ninth government to be banned from receiving new
loans from the fund.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Army Copter Grounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army has again grounded its fleet of AH-64
Apache attack helicopters, this time while it investigates the cause
of a crash in Florida last week.
   The Apache is the nation's most sophisticated helicopter gunship.
The Army now has 486 of them.
   The grounding announced Monday came in the wake of last week's
crash in northern Florida of an Apache gunship assigned to the
Florida National Guard. The co-pilot was killed and the pilot was
seriously injured when the tail rotor came off.
   The Apache fleet was last grounded in August 1987 while
investigators studied the failure of one component of the tail
rotor. The Army said Monday, however, it had already ruled out that
problem as a factor in last week's crash. The Apache fleet was
grounded twice in 1986, both times for relatively minor problems.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<UNK>Study Calls for Change in Weapon Purchases</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration should create a weapons
``procurement corps'' separate from the Pentagon to eliminate
conflicts of interest in purchasing weapons, a study suggests.
   The study was released Monday by Ralph Nader's Center for Study
of Responsive Law.
   The study cited varying reasons for the Pentagon's weapons
problems, including overreliance on new technologies, insufficient
testing, inadequate competition and a ``revolving door'' between the
Pentagon procurement system and private defense contractors.
   It also blamed members of Congress for judging new weapons
projects on the potential economic payoff for their own state or
district rather than the actual need for the weapons.
</TEXT>
