</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tinny song of the Good Humor man has
kids screaming for ice cream, but their parents are getting tired of
paying the piper, especially before meals.
   ``The ice-cream truck invariably comes by right before dinner,
which is when kids are hungry and tired and cranky,'' said Linda
Lowenstein, who presented a petition to the city council asking that
ice cream truck music be banned.
   ``It sets up a situation where the kids are adversaries with the
parents,'' according to environmental enforcement officer Terry
Steinborn, who said the council is considering lowering the
allowable noise from the trucks to 55 decibels, about the same as
normal conversation.
   The ordinance was suggested by frustrated parents who are tired
of battling their children at dinnertime over the merits of
chocolate chip vs. peas and carrots. Forty people complained about
the ice-cream song in 1988.
   The existing limit is 80 decibels. Ice-cream trucks with music
have been measured at 70 to 90 decibels.
   Only one company, Ice Cream Wagon Inc. of Commerce City, operates
an ice-cream truck with music in Boulder, Steinborn said.
   Company owner Joe Saurini has said operating an ice-cream truck
without music would be ``like climbing mountains without shoes.''
   Loewenstein, a columnist for the Boulder Daily Camera, said
Friday, ``I realize it's fun for the kids to go out to the ice-cream
man, take their money out and be their own little bosses. I don't
think it's evil; it's just annoying.''
</TEXT>
