<FIRST>r a PM-OrionAir     07-04 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Orion Air,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Facing Bad PR Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F. ALAN BOYCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The repair-related delays that caused
hundreds of would-be passengers to cancel trips on two Orion Air
flights cast unfavorable light on an airline that has come under
fire in recent years.
   On Sunday, 167 passengers in Manchester, England, got refunds
when they refused to travel to Florida on an Orion jumbo jet delayed
for two days by three mechanical problems, said Roy Edwards, manager
of the Manchester Airport. The incident came four days after 53
British tourists refused to reboard a Hawaii-bound Orion jet after
it was forced to land in Edmonton, Alberta on a repair stop.
   An Orion employee reached at the Raleigh headquarters Monday said
Robert Bushman, president and chief executive officer, was
unavailable for comment. Other officials did not return the phone
call.
   Orion was involved in a 1988 lawsuit for training non-union
pilots in anticipation of a strike at Eastern Airlines, and the
Federal Aviation Administration fined the airline for 2,000 safety
violations.
   Eastern was then embroiled in a dispute with its machinists over
the airline's demand for a $50 million cut in annual labor costs.
   Orion, then the largest operator of jet aircraft for the small
package industry, asked the FAA for permission to become a passenger
carrier to fly some Eastern planes in the event of a strike.
   Eastern and Orion entered into a $50 million-a-year contract
calling for Orion to hire 400 flight attendants, 300 pilots and 100
mechanics to cover about 10 percent of Eastern's fleet.
   The pact came at a good time for Orion, which was then phasing
out a $32 million-a-year contract to fly and maintain planes for
United Parcel Service of America Inc. UPS, which had provided about
half of Orion's business, decided to fly and maintain its own
aircraft.
   As Orion sought FAA approval for passenger service, an FAA
inspection report said the airline had more than 2,000 safety
infractions from its cargo operation.
   The agency listed a shortage of required training records,
inadequate auditing of maintenance facilities, poor documentation on
the qualifications of ``check pilots'' who decide on the performance
of line pilots and incomplete flight operations manuals.
   Orion officials during congressional hearings said many of the
concerns stemmed from a misunderstanding about Orion's methods of
record keeping and that all of the concerns had been resolved.
   In March 1988, the Air Line Pilots Association sucessfully sued
to prevent Orion from operating flights for Eastern, saying such
subcontracting would violate the union's contract with Eastern.
   The next month, the FAA proposed $636,200 in fines against Orion
for violations uncovered during inspections of the airline. Orion
paid the penalty and officials said all the violations had been
corrected.
   Eastern announced in May 1988 that it had canceled its contract
with Orion. The cancellation cost Eastern about $5.5 million under a
provision of the Orion contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
