<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-RoevsWade     07-04 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Roe vs Wade,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roe Attorney Says Future of Abortion Rests With Young Adults</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus-Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2, DN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney who argued the case that
legalized abortions and the ``Jane Roe'' she represented said they
were crushed by the Supreme Court's abortion decision but pledged to
fight for the right to choose.
   The attorney who opposed them saw Monday's ruling upholding
Missouri regulations limiting abortion rights as a sign that Roe vs.
Wade would be overturned.
   Attorney Sarah Weddington, who represented Jane Roe, said she had
expected the high court to only ``whittle away'' at its 1973 Roe vs.
Wade decision that legalized abortions.
   ``I did not expect what they did and that was to chop away at
that decision,'' said Ms. Weddington, 44.
   ``I've invested 20 years of my life in this and now have been
handed a major defeat.''
   Her former client Norma McCorvey, a Dallas cleaning woman who
took the pseudonym Jane Roe in the landmark case, said she was angry
about the high court's ruling.
   ``We will keep fighting so that no woman will ever be maimed or
killed by an unsafe, illegal abortion,'' she told reporters in Los
Angeles.
   ``This is a critical time for all pro-choice and pro-family women
and men,'' she said. ``We must link arm and arm to protect and
uphold the right to safe and legal abortion.''
   Nevertheless, McCorvey added: ``To the Supreme Court of the
United States, thank you for not reversing Roe vs. Wade.''
   Jay Floyd, who as an assistant state attorney general faced Ms.
Weddington in the Supreme Court 17 years ago, said he was pleased by
the Missouri ruling.
   ``I think ultimately they are going to overrule Roe vs. Wade or
chip away to where it has no meaning,'' said Floyd, who has been in
private practice in the central Texas town of Llano for the past 10
years.
   Floyd's old boss at the attorney general's office, Robert
Flowers, agreed.
   ``It appears this decision is sort of a prelude to putting some
further restrictions on abortion rights,'' said Flowers, who argued
the state's case before the Supreme Court in 1972 when the justices
had oral arguments repeated before issuing Roe vs. Wade.
   Ms. Weddington said the issue rests with young adults, but she
pledged to continue to speak out. She said abortion supporters must
lobby their state legislatures.
   ``If people don't really say, `No we're not going to have this,'
if they don't lobby their own state legislatures,'' abortion will
become illegal, Ms. Weddington told reporters at Texas Woman's
University, where she is an adjunct professor.
   Earlier Monday, McCorvey, 41, appeared on the Cable News Network
show ``Sonya Live in LA,'' and said she took Monday's ruling ``very
personally.''
   ``It saddens my heart very deeply to know that poor women are
once again going to be out there going to backstreet abortions and
possibly be mutilated and not have the right to choose,'' she said.
   In 1969, McCorvey, unmarried, unemployed and pregnant, asked her
family doctor for an abortion, which was illegal in Texas. Her
doctor refused, and she didn't like what she saw at an illegal
abortion clinic, spurring the lawsuit.
   By the time the Supreme Court ruled, McCorvey had given birth to
a daughter and had given the child up for adoption. In 1971, she had
another child, whom she also gave up for adoption.
</TEXT>
