<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpills     07-04 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spills,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crabbing Banned in Delaware River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial crabbing was banned over a 22-mile
stretch of the Delaware River after oil-soaked crustaceans were
pulled out of the water near where a tanker ran aground and spilled
300,000 gallons of heating oil.
   Delaware's top environmental official, Edwin ``Toby'' Clark II
imposed the ban Monday from the Pennsylvania-Delaware line to the
southern tip of Pea Patch Island off Delaware City. He said the step
was necessary to protect the Delaware Bay's $1.5 million crabbing
industry.
   Meanwhile, the Greek tanker that spilled 420,000 gallons of
heating oil off Rhode Island on June 23 arrived Monday evening at a
New York shipyard for repairs.
   Aerial inspections showed no oil leaking from the World Prodigy
as it traveled from Rhode Island to the New York Shipyard Corp., the
Coast Guard said.
   The crabbing ban covers most of the area affected by a oil spill
June 24, when the Uruguayan tanker Presidente Rivera ran aground
just below the state line near Claymont, dumping 306,684 gallons of
heating oil into the river.
   The ban was expected to last about three weeks, said Roger Lucio,
spokesman for the Department of Natural Resources and Environmental
Control.
   ``The order serves as a precautionary measure to ensure no
oil-tainted crabs are placed on the market,'' Lucio said.
   Oil-covered crabs were first pulled from the river by commercial
watermen on Saturday. The watermen were then advised to crab south
of the island. The advisory remained in effect after the ban was
imposed.
   Coast Guard Lt. James Weakley said there were no reports of
oil-covered crabs off New Jersey.
   Cleanup efforts continued along the riverbanks of Delaware,
Pennsylvania and New Jersey. Weakley said there were ``negligible
amounts of free-floating oil in the water.''
   The Coast Guard estimated 75 percent to 80 percent of the oil had
been cleaned up.
</TEXT>
