<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-04 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange edged down
Tuesday, while the dollar was sharply lower against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar ended trading at 140.95 yen, down 1.55 yen from
Monday's 142.50-yen close. The currency opened at 141.28 yen and
fluctuated between 140.45 yen and 141.50 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 46.04
points, or 0.14 percent, ending the day at 33,190.38. The index had
gained 287.73 points the previous day.
   Nomura Securities analyst Masahiro Umemori said Japanese
investors' buying incentive was weak due to the governing Liberal
Democratic Party's election loss and concerns over the upcoming
national election for the upper house of Parliament.
   In Sunday's election for 128 seats in the Tokyo Metropolitan
Assembly, the LDP kept only 43 seats, losing 20 from last year's 63,
while the Japan Socialist Party's strength rose from 12 to 29 seats.
   Sunday's election was taken as an indicator of the upper house
election scheduled for July 23.
   ``Many participants were just sitting on the sidelines today,''
Umemori said.
   In currency dealings, Japanese investors were taking profits by
selling dollars they had bought ahead of Sunday's election in Tokyo,
expecting a poor performance from the LDP, traders said.
   But the yen is not likely to rise further because of Japan's
continuing political uncertainties, especially before the upper
house election, said a trader with major commercial bank, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Many investors avoided major moves because the New York market
was closed for the U.S. Independence Day holiday Tuesday, he added.
</TEXT>
