<FIRST>r i PM-Guatemala-Strike     07-04 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guatemala-Strike,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Police Break Up Demonstration by Striking Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Club-wielding riot police broke up a
demonstration by about 300 striking teachers and supporters, driving
them away from the National Palace, authorities said. Witnesses said
police beat some of the protesters.
   Guillermo Mollinedo, a National Police spokesman, said at least
18 people were arrested in Monday's protest.
   Witnesses said police beat an undetermined number of people they
arrested and pushed into police vehicles.
   About 37,000 elementary and junior high school teachers entered
the fifth week of a strike Monday to demand higher salaries and
other benefits. Their walkout has kept about 1 million students from
school.
   They scheduled another demonstration for today, and it was
expected to draw thousands of teachers from the provinces.
   A separate strike has paralyzed telegraph and postal service.
   At the National Palace on Monday night, police charged a crowd
that was chanting support for 42 teachers who went inside to try to
discuss their demands with Education Minister Ricardo Galvez Gomez,
authorities said.
   Galvez Gomez has asked the courts to declare the strike illegal
and threatened to begin firing those who refuse to return to work.
   Some junior high students blocked traffic and burned tires in the
street Monday, saying they oppose both the strike and the government
position and want only to return to school.
   Authorities have said the end of the school year may be extended
from October to December if the strike does not end soon.
   Teachers are demanding raises of $80 a month. Elementary school
teachers now earn about $225 a month and middle-level teachers $310.
</TEXT>
