<FIRST>r a PM-AtlantaFire     07-04 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atlanta Fire,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifth Victim Dies; Building Called `Fire Trap' in 1982</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fifth victim has died of injuries suffered in a
fire at a 10-story office building that an investigator warned seven
years ago was a firetrap.
   Fire officials said Monday their investigation of last week's
blaze continues to point to an electrical worker who apparently
triggered an explosion while changing a fuse. The electrician died
in the blast.
   Office worker Eudora Rodgers, 48, died Monday at Piedmont
Hospital. She and three other office workers who died succumbed to
smoke inhalation during the fire. More than 30 people were injured.
   Mona Watkins, a fellow office employee, said Ms. Rodgers had
guided her to a window before collapsing.
   ``As we were getting close, I felt her hand fall away _ we
couldn't see each other, the smoke was too thick,'' Ms. Watkins said.
   Acting Fire Chief Tom Perrin said a fire inspector examined the
Peachtree 25th Building in July 1982 and concluded that a fire could
be disastrous in the structure, which was built in 1962 and had no
sprinklers.
   ``When he conducted his investigation some years back, he felt
like it was a fire trap,'' Perrin said. The investigator, now a fire
company lieutenant, suggested changes, Perrin said.
   ``Four lives could have been saved if there had been sprinklers
in there,'' Perrin said before Ms. Rodgers' died.
   The building was renovated in July 1982, but it wasn't known if
fire code changes were made, said Deputy Chief A.D. Bell. Sprinkler
systems have been required in new buildings over eight stories tall
since 1974.
   ``We're still looking at how much renovation was conducted at
that time, and that would determine what type of codes would have to
be abided by,'' Bell said.
   Perrin said the lieutenant reminded him of the 1982 inspection
some hours after the fire at the midtown office building. The
lieutenant has since left on vacation and will be questioned further
when he returns, Perrin said.
   American Management Co. of Torrance, Calif., which manages the
Peachtree 25th building, referred reporters to a representative in
its Atlanta office, who did not return a reporter's telephone call
Monday.
</TEXT>
