<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine-Suit     07-04 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line-Suit,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adams Sues Producer of Film That Led to His Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randall Dale Adams is suing the producer of the
``Thin Blue Line,'' the movie that helped win his release from
prison after 12 years and exoneration from a murder conviction.
   Producer Errol Morris said he is ``hurt and upset'' by the
lawsuit, in which Adams is seeking to gain film rights to his life
story.
   District Judge Felix Salazar on Monday postponed a hearing on the
suit because the defendants filed a motion to move the proceedings
to federal court.
   The suit contends that Morris lost his rights to Adams' life
story in December 1988, when he failed to exercise a two-year option
purchased from Adams for $10 in December 1986.
   An appeals court overturned Adams conviction after he served 12
years in prison following his conviction in the shooting death of
Dallas policeman Robert Wood. Adams was freed from prison in March
and Dallas County prosecutors declined to try him again.
   ``I worked very, very hard for a number of years to see that
justice was done in this case and to see that Randall Adams walked
out of prison,'' Morris said.
   The producer said his profits from the film, which was not widely
distributed, were ``nil.'' He said he is still paying off debts from
the movie.
   ``The simple thing is that when I met Randall Adams, nobody cared
about the case, no one wanted to investigate it, no one wanted to
write about it,'' Morris said.
   Adams, 40, is not seeking royalties, said his lawyer, Randy
Schaffer.
   He said Adams wants a declaration that he owns the right to his
own life story. That would enable him to pursue offers Schaffer
estimated ``in the neighborhood of six figures.''
   ``They think they bought (Adams) lock, stock and barrel for $10,
and that's unconscionable,'' Schaffer said. ``He is grateful, but
what is he supposed to do? He's got offers to do a book and a
movie.''
   Schaffer said Morris has claimed he did exercise the option to
purchase Adams' story and has resold the rights to Mirimax
Production Co., also a defendant.
   Adams reportedly was en route from his home in Ohio to Houston
and could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
