<FIRST>r i PM-China-PornClassic     07-04 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Porn Classic,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unabridged Version of 16th Century Pornographic Classic Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unabridged edition of China's 16th-century
pornographic classic, ``The Golden Lotus,'' has been published after
being banned for 40 years by the Communist government.
   The official Xinhua News Agency reported today that 8,000 copies
of the bawdy tale about a philandering merchant and his six wives
were printed, but said they would be distributed only to professors
of Chinese language and ``Golden Lotus'' researchers.
   The report did not say if more printings were planned.
   The book was printed from a master copy of the work stored in the
Beijing University library, the news agency said. It said the book
contains 200 pictures, but did not describe them.
   An abridged version of the book was published two years ago, but
censors cut out more than 10,000 words on the sexual perambulations
of the merchant, Jing Xiwen. Even so, more than 10,000 copies were
immediately sold out.
   The Communist government banned the novel in 1949 because of its
explicit sexual descriptions.
   Besides being a tale of sex that far outdoes most modern erotica,
``The Golden Lotus'' is China's earliest novel describing the lives
of ordinary people in believable terms.
   It also is the first novel to focus on female characters and the
first book to be written in the vernacular.
</TEXT>
