<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     07-04 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>50 Villages Hit by Floods, Two Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flash floods swept through 50 villages
and drowned at least two people after heavy rains forced tributaries
of the Brahmaputra River over their banks, officials said today.
   The floods began Monday in the northern and eastern regions of
the country after monsoon rains swelled the rivers, Relief Ministry
officials said. They said at least 50 villages were flooded, and
rice crops were damaged.
   At least two people were washed away by rising water in the
Bandarban district 150 miles southeast of Dhaka, police in the area
said.
   Sangbad, a Dhaka-based newspaper, said at least 20,000 people
were marooned by the floods in the northern district of Rangpur. It
said they took refuge on high ground or roofs.
   Bangladesh, a low-lying country of 110 million people, is
criss-crossed by hundreds of rivers that form the deltas of the
Brahmaputra and the Ganges rivers. The summer monsoons usually cause
flooding.
   Last year, floods inundated about four-fifths of Bangladesh, and
at least 1,400 people were killed. At least 2.3 million people were
left homeless.
