<SECOND>PM-Plant Explosion,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed, Two Injured in Plant Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fiery explosion in a chemical mixing vat
killed three workers and injured two, authorities said.
   A team from the U.S. Occupational Health and Safety Agency was
expected to arrive today to investigate, said Hugh Hillhouse, site
manager of the chemical division of the Minnesota Mining and
Manufacturing Co. plant.
   The vat that exploded Monday was used in the manufacture of two
different chemicals _ Fluorel and Kel-F _ that are part of the
production of high-temperature gaskets, said Hillhouse.
   The fatal accident was the 3M plant's first in its 27 years at
the Decatur site, he said.
   Hillhouse said damage could reach more than $100,000. The section
where the explosion occurred was expected to be closed for weeks.
The rest of the plant, which employs more than 1,000 people, was
expected to be open today.
   Hillhouse and officials from the Morgan County Emergency
Management Agency said no hazardous chemicals were believed to have
escaped into the atmosphere due to the fire, which took about 45
minutes to control.
   Killed were John T. Crawford, 46, of Somerville; Jerry Lloyd
Wilkerson, 49, of Trinity; and James Michael Martin, 36, of Athens.
   Martin was a 12-year production employee; Wilkerson and Crawford,
both maintenance workers, each had at least 25 years with the
company.
   The two injured were taken to Parkway Medical Center, where one
was treated and released and the other was admitted for a head
injury. His condition was not released.
</TEXT>
