<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-04 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued its fall against the Japanese
yen today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index edged down.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 46.04
points, or 0.14 percent, closing at 33,190.38.
   Yoshio Shimoyama, a dealer at Nikko Securities, said Japanese
investors were reluctant to buy shares amid political uncertainties
over the July 23 election for the upper house of Parliament.
   ``Although the Nikkei fell, certain issues were bought as the
yen's appreciation reassured investors,'' he said. ``Trading was
also more active than yesterday.''
   First section volume was estimated at 550 million shares, up from
Monday's 300 million. Electrical issues attracted buyers.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 140.95 yen, down 1.55
yen from Monday's 142.50-yen close. It opened at 141.28 yen and
fluctuated between 140.45 yen and 141.50 yen. The dollar now has
fallen 3.00 yen in two trading days.
   The dollar was being sold on a number of markets, partly due to
expectations that the United States might ease its monetary policy,
said Yoshitsugu Hanada, a trader with Mitsui Bank in Tokyo.
   ``But the dollar-selling drive was weaker today than the one that
forced the currency rate to fall from 151.30 yen a couple of weeks
ago,'' he said.
   The dollar closed at 151.30 yen on June 15, but fell 6.25 yen the
next day.
   Hanada said dollar-selling for profit-taking and reported
intervention by the Bank of Japan also helped push the dollar down
today, although investors were avoiding major moves while the New
York market was closed for the Independence Day holiday.
   The central bank does not comment on its foreign exchange market
activities.
   ``Japanese investors sold the dollar to reduce their
dollar-holding positions because they had bought too much before the
Tokyo Metropolitan Assembly election,'' Hanada said.
   Investors had been buying dollars out of pessimism over the
governing Liberal Democratic Party's prospects in Sunday's voting,
he said.
   In the election for 128 seats in the Tokyo Metropolitan Assembly,
the LDP kept only 43 seats, a loss of 20, while the Japan Socialist
Party's strength rose from 12 to 29 seats.
   The election was taken as an indicator of how voting would go in
the July upper house election.
</TEXT>
