<SECOND>PM-Mel Blanc,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mel Blanc, Voice of Bugs Bunny, In Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mel Blanc, the voice behind such cartoon
characters as Bugs Bunny, Porky Pig, Sylvester the cat, Barney
Rubble and Dino the Dinosaur, was listed in serious condition today,
hospital officials said.
   Blanc, 81, entered Cedars Sinai Medical Center on May 19 and was
being treated for heart and other problems, hospital spokesman Ron
Wise said.
   His condition remained serious for the past week.
   ``He is being very carefully watched,'' Wise said.
   Since 1937, Blanc provided the voices for many Warner Bros.
cartoon characters, including Daffy Duck, Tweety-Pie and Yosemite
Sam.
   He is perhaps best known for Bugs Bunny's wisecracking ``What's
up Doc?'' Sylvester's ``Thufferin' thuccotash!,'' and Porky Pig's
stuttering ``Th-th-th-that's all folks.''
   He also created Woody Woodpecker's staccato laugh, the Road
Runner's nonchalant ``beep-beep,'' and Fred Flintstone's pet
dinosaur Dino's bark and Barney Rubble's voice.
   He was a regular on ``The Jack Benny Show,'' playing Professor
LeBlanc, Benny's violin teacher and the train dispatcher who
announced the stops of ``Ana-heim, A-zusa and KOOK-amunga!''
   Blanc also was Sy the Mexican gardener and made the sputtering
sounds of Benny's ancient Maxwell automobile.
   In later years, he brought his dozens of voices to numerous
commercials and gave life to many Saturday morning cartoon
characters.
</TEXT>
