<HEAD>Bomb Explosion Kills Seven, Injures 24</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in a bus today in a
crowded market section of this city near the Afghan border, killing
seven people and injuring 24, police officials said.
   The majority of the victims were Afghan nationals, said police.
   The bomb, apparently placed in the rear of the bus, exploded
shortly before noon in the crowded Khyber Bazaar. Witnesses said
windows in nearby shops shattered.
   No one claimed responsibility. Police said they had not made any
arrests and refused to speculate on suspects.
   Hundreds of explosions have ripped through Peshawar over the past
several years, killing scores of people and injuring hundreds.
   The government has blamed the bombings on Afghan government
agents.
   More than 3 million Afghan war refugees live in Pakistan, which
also headquarters U.S.-backed Afghan guerrillas, who have been
fighting for more than a decade to oust Kabul's ruling communists.
   Peshawar, at the foot of the famed Khyber Pass, is only about 40
miles east of the Afghan border. It is encircled by sprawling dust
bowls of adobe huts that house the majority of Afghan refugees
living in Pakistan.
