<FIRST>u i PM-Baker 1stLd-Writethru a0451 07-04 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan, Western Europe Pledge Philippine Aid at U.S. Request</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with aid pledges by Japan, Western
Europe; picks up 12th pvs `The theory...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With encouragement from Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, Japan and Western Europe today pledged increases in aid
to the Philippines totaling about $335 million as part of an
ambitious international effort to bolster the country's
three-year-old democracy.
   Japanese Foreign Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzaka promised an increase
of about $101 million in aid over the $899 million it committed in
the past year.
   French Ambassador Bernard Dorin, speaking for the 12-nation
European Economic Community, said the EEC would chip in the
equivalent of $350 million, up from $117 million.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Mangaplus of the Philippines praised the
donors for their ``solemn act of humanitarian justice'' and said all
loans would be paid back.
   Earlier, Baker spoke to the conference, convened by the World
Bank, shortly after arriving from Washington. Delegations from 19
countries and seven international groups have assembled to discuss
the program, known as the Multilateral Assistance Initiative.
   It envisions a five-year program involving $10 billion in aid and
private investment for the Philippines.
   Baker said the initiative is critical to the future of
Philippines democracy. The Bush administration is asking for $200
million from Congress as its first year contribution.
   Combined with other aid requests, the administration hopes to
provide the Philippines with $658 million in economic assistance in
fiscal 1990.
   The convening of the meeting symbolizes a significant expansion
in the sharing of responsibility for the Philippines' well-being.
   Previously, the United States accounted for the bulk of foreign
aid to the its former colony, but Japan is now the largest donor.
   Baker said that despite significant economic growth in recent
years in the Philippines, ``enormous problems of poverty and
development persist _ problems that challenge us all to this very
special effort.''
   Average incomes are still well below their 1981 levels, he said.
The political upheavals of the mid-1980s, which drove out the
government of Ferdinand Marcos, devastated the Filipino economy.
   In addition, the government of President Corazon Aquino is
battling a 20-year-old communist insurgency.
   The theory behind the new initiative is that the Philippines will
be able to achieve its economic potential only through a coordinated
effort in which outside capital, economic reform and an improved
private investment climate all have key roles.
   Baker arrived in Tokyo at a time of renewed political crisis in
Japan, brought on by electoral setbacks suffered by the governing
Liberal Democrats and allegations that Prime Minister Sosuke Uno has
kept several paid mistresses.
   En route here, Baker declined comment on Uno's problems, saying
the United States must ``studiously avoid'' involvement in Japan's
internal political affairs.
   Baker and Uno were to have dinner tonight.
   After a day-long stay in Tokyo, Baker heads for Brunei, where he
is to meet with colleagues from the six-nation Association of
Southeast Asian Nations.
   The talks are to focus on ways to promote an accord among rival
factions in Cambodia once the Vietnamese complete the scheduled
withdrawal of their forces in September.
</TEXT>
