<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-04 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slides, Gold Strengthens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slid in early European trading today and
foreign currency dealers said some market participants were trying
to push it through key levels. Gold prices strengthened.
   Trading was quiet because of the Fourth of July holiday in the
United States.
   Dealers in West Germany said dollar sellers were running into
lots of buyers as the U.S. currency approaches 1.9150 marks.
   ``That level looks really good on the chart,'' said a trader at a
major U.S. bank in Frankfurt. ``It doesn't look like we're going to
break through it today.''
   Others said the dollar's slide was also due to rumors the Bank of
Japan intervened in earlier East Asian trading and to anticipation
of lower U.S. interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.55 yen to a closing 140.95 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 141.38 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.9196 West German marks, down from 1.9285
   _1.6485 Swiss francs, down from 1.65375
   _6.5235 French francs, down from 6.5485
   _2.1633 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1775
   _1,389.50 Italian lire, up@down from 1,400.50
   _1.1920 Canadian dollars, down from 1.19455
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5880 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5775 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $378.15 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $375.05. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $377.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $377.00, up from $374.35 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.38 to close at a bid $378.31.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.27 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $5.20.
</TEXT>
