<FIRST>u i PM-Solzhenitsyn 1stLd-Writethru a0490 07-04 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solzhenitsyn, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writer's Union Votes to Restore Solzhenitsyn's Membership</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official writers' union has voted to reinstate
Alexander Solzhenitsyn, the dissident chronicler of Stalinist terror
who was expelled from the Soviet Union in 1974, a newspaper said
today.
   Literaturnaya Gazeta, the weekly newspaper of the Union of Soviet
Writers, said that the group's 26-member secretariat voted to revoke
what it called his ``wrongful'' 1969 expulsion.
   The paper said his ouster contradicted ``the principles of
socialist democracy.'' The writers' union also urged the government
to restore his citizenship, Literaturnaya Gazeta said.
   The 168-word article, which appeared midway down the front page,
did not say when the union took its action.
   The restoration follows the report in April that the leading
Soviet literary journal, Novy Mir, will publish excerpts of
Solzhenitsyn's major work, ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' by year's end.
   The work chronicles life in Soviet labor camps, mostly under
dictator Josef Stalin. Solzhenitzyn was freed from the camps after
Stalin's death in 1953.
   The works of Solzhenitsyn, who won the Nobel Prize for Literature
in 1970, have not been published in his homeland since Novy Mir
carried his short novel ``One Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich''
in November 1962 during a cultural thaw under Nikita S. Khrushchev.
   The thaw ended shortly thereafter, and Solzhenitsyn's works were
banned.
   Although Soviet literary officials have authorized publication of
part of ``Gulag,'' it is not clear whether they will clear portions
of the book blaming the founder of Soviet state, Vladimir Lenin, for
initiating terror in the Soviet Union.
   Solzhenitsyn lives with his family in seclusion in Cavendish, Vt.
</TEXT>
