<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-04 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms and Hail Over the Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms doused North Dakota and Nebraska today and
floodwaters were waist-high at one South Carolina crossroads.
   Rain continued in central Louisiana, where rivers were submerging
their banks and authorities expected flooding for at least two weeks.
   Thunderstorms dumped golf ball-size hail at Custer, S.D., and
Fremont County, Colo., Monday night and heavy storms swept from
Nebraska to Wisconsin.
   A tornado was spotted east of Huron, S.D., and hail the size of
gum drops fell in Kimball.
   Thunderstorms over eastern Wisconsin deluged Fond du Lac with
half an inch of rain in just ten minutes, with wind gusts of up to
46 mph.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms extended this morning
along much of the Gulf and Mid Atlantic coasts and into the Ohio
Valley.
   A storm in central Alabama flooded the streets of Aliceville and
left water waist deep at Tokeena Crossroads in western South
Carolina.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hour period ending at 2 a.m.
EDT included nearly two inches at Crossville, Tenn., 1.83 inches at
Columbus, Ga., and 0.35 inches at Cincinnati.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 93 degrees at Phoenix.
   The Independence Day forecast called for showers and
thunderstorms scattered from eastern Texas across the Gulf Coast,
Tennessee and Ohio valleys east to the Atlantic Coast. Rain showers
were likely over western Washington state. Sunny skies were expected
for most of the rest of the nation.
   The mercury was to rise above 100 in the Rio Grande Valley; above
110 over the desert Southwest. Highs in the 90s were forecast over
southern Georgia and Florida, in the Mississippi Valley across the
Plains and the Rockies into interior California; in the 60s and 70s
from northern Idaho into Washington and along the Pacific Coast; in
the 80s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
