<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Kadar     07-04 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Kadar,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Hungarian Leader in Critical Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Hungarian leader Janos Kadar was
in critical condition after he was hospitalized with pneumonia as
well as breathing and circulatory problems, a radio report said
today.
   Communist party chairman Rezso Nyers and general secretary Karoly
Grosz visited him in the hospital today, Radio Kossuth reported.
   The brief report said Kadar's condition had turned critical but
gave no details. Party spokesman Emil Kimmel said a medical report
would be issued later today.
   Kadar, 77, was stripped of all his party posts in May after he
was reported gravely ill.
   He was named honorary chairman of the ruling Hungarian Socialist
Workers' Party in May 1988 after Grosz replaced him as party leader.
Kadar held that post for 32 years.
   Since losing the party leadership, Kadar has seen his political
legacy increasingly questioned.
   After guiding Hungary to relative prosperity and tolerance by the
1970s, he was seen as an obstacle to political and economic reform
in the 1980s.
   He has not been seen in public since April, when participants at
a communist Central Committee meeting said he gave a long, rambling
speech.
   In recent interviews, Kadar was quoted as saying the fate of Imre
Nagy and other leaders of the 1956 Hungarian revolt was his
``personal tragedy.''
   Kadar came to power after Soviet troops and tanks crushed the
uprising, and Nagy and his associates were executed on charges of
high treason in 1958 after a Stalinist show trial.
   Nagy and other uprising leaders were honored as national martyrs
at a reburial ceremony June 16 after what amounted to a political
rehabilitation of Nagy and a re-evaluation of the uprising.
</TEXT>
