<FIRST>r i PM-PalmeTrial     07-04 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme Trial,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Killing Swedish Leader Refuses More Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of killing Prime
Minister Olof Palme refused to answer further questions in court
today, charging that prosecutors were unfairly trying to convict him.
   ``It does not matter what questions you ask, so I will not answer
your questions,'' said Christer Pettersson, a 42-year-old Swede.
   Pettersson has denied killing Palme, a four-term prime minister
who was assassinated on Feb. 28, 1986.
   Looking pale and tired, Pettersson interrupted when prosecutor
Anders Helin was about to start questioning him for a second time.
Pettersson testified on the opening day of the trial in Stockholm
District Court on June 5.
   ``You have done everything to cast doubt on witnesses supporting
my case. Imagine if you had carried out such careful investigations
with the other witnesses,'' Pettersson said.
   He was apparently referring to tough cross-examination Monday of
a defense witness who supported his alibi that he was in a train
station 18 miles away at the time of the shooting.
   The court cannot force a defendant to testify.
   Palme's widow, Lisbeth, has identified Pettersson as the man she
saw rush away after her husband was shot while the couple walked
home from a downtown movie.
   Earlier today, defense attorney Arne Liljeros tried to discredit
Mrs. Palme's testimony by questioning Stig Engstrom, one of the
first bystanders to rush up to the dying Palme.
   Engstrom, an insurance company employee, said Mrs. Palme appeared
``confused and disoriented ... but I was able to talk to her.''
   The prosecutors also showed a five-minute videotape of police
surveillance of Pettersson before his arrest in December. It showed
him walking with a limp, matching Mrs. Palme's initial account of
the man she saw escaping.
   Mrs. Palme has said she never saw Pettersson holding a gun.
   The prosecutors have built their case around her identification
and other witnesses who said they saw Pettersson nearby. The murder
weapon has not been found, and no clear motive has been established.
   Pettersson has a history of violent crime and drug abuse.
   Final arguments were scheduled to start Thursday.
</TEXT>
