<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 0941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-04 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Lift Land Siege; Syrians and Christians Duel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Druse militiamen lifted a 16-week land
siege of Lebanon's Christian-held region today after Syrian gunners
and Lebanese Christian forces traded rocket and artillery fire that
killed one person.
   Syrian troops fired a barrage of howitzers early today in
maintaining its sea blockade of the Christian enclave. A local
newspaper reported Syria is tightening that blockade.
   Lifting the land siege appears to be a guarded response to an
Iraqi offer Sunday to halt arms shipments to the Christians if Syria
stops besieging them. Iraq, Syria's main Arab rival, is the main
backer of Gen. Michel Aoun, who leads the Christian Cabinet.
   Beirut International Airport, which Moslem leaders said would
reopen at noon, was not ready to receive aircraft. Repair crews
worked on runways and terminals damaged by shellfire and rockets.
   Police said one person was killed and five were wounded in
shelling that stopped 35 minutes before Beirut's Museum crossing and
the Madfoun gateway, linking the Christian region with
Syrian-policed north Lebanon, reopened around midday.
   Hundreds of pedestrians and motorists flooded the Museum crossing
after Moslem troops lifted containers and knocked down earthmounds
blocking the gateway at the Green Line dividing Beirut into Moslem
and Christian sectors.
   Many travelers, some carrying food and other supplies, cried for
joy as Moslem units of the Lebanese army ushered them across to
Christian east Beirut.
   ``They didn't take away the vegetables. This is the first time in
more than three months they allow me to carry vegetables to east
Beirut,'' cried one woman, her eyes brimming with tears.
   Troops frisked pedestrians and searched cars for weapons.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem Cabinet in
the dual government, said lifting the land siege and reopening the
airport are ``a basic step toward resolving the crisis.''
   There was no comment on today's developments from Aoun.
   He met with the ambassadors of the United States, France and
Britain to complain about the sea blockade and was to meet the
Chinese and Soviet envoys later today.
   More than 1 million Christians were trapped by the blockade and
siege. By police count, 397 people have been killed and 1,538
wounded since March 8, when Druse fighters retaliated against Aoun's
blockading of illegal ports run by them and other Syrian-backed
Moslem militias.
   Syrian troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate backed the Druse militiamen of warlord Walid Jumblatt and
joined the battle to ensure the blockade.
   Aoun has pledged to oust the Syrian troops from Lebanon. But he
has only about 20,000 fighters while Syria deploys 40,000 troops in
the country and can call on allied militias that command another
40,000 fighters.
   The prestigious daily newspaper An-Nahar today said Syria has
tightened its sea blockade. It said a gunboat on Monday intercepted
a ship carrying passengers and cargo from south Lebanon to the
northern port of Jounieh.
   ``A Syrian officer boarded the ship and searched it for weapons.
When he found only food supplies and passengers, the officer warned
the vessel's Egyptian captain not to use the route again,'' the
paper said.
</TEXT>
