<SECOND>PM-Soviet Fighter Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0500,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0515 to fix overline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Mig-23 Crashes in Belgium, One Person Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with one reported killed, U.S., West
German comment. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KORTRIJK, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet MiG-23 fighter jet today
crashed into a house near the French border, killing one person,
officials said. The pilot apparently had bailed out.
   Two U.S. Air Force F-15 jets intercepted the plane after it
crossed into Western European airspace and escorted it until it
crashed.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Gaston Bourlet said the plane crashed
at 10:37 a.m. in Wevelgem, a town on the French border about 50
miles west of Brussels.
   Emmanuel de Bethune, mayor of the nearby town of Kortrijk, said
an 18-year-old man was killed when the plane crashed into a bedroom
of his home.
   The whereabouts of the pilot were unknown. Nor was it known from
where the combat plane had taken off or what weapons it carried.
   Bourlet said the MiG-23 had entered Belgium near the Dutch-German
border, 125 miles from the crash site. Officials said it was
monitored crossing into West German airspace from East Germany and
failed to respond to radio calls.
   In Washington, a Defense Department spokesman, Air Force Maj.
Mike Stepp, said two F-15s from Soesterberg Air Base in the
Netherlands intercepted the aircraft, which ``had no canopy and no
pilot.''
   Asked what happened to the Soviet pilot, the spokesman said that
wasn't immediately clear, but it appeared he must have ejected from
the plane. ``I have to assume the aircraft didn't take off by
itself,'' he said.
   The Belgian news agency Belga said the MiG-23 had taken off from
East Germany. A West German Defense Ministry official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said he was ``assuming that the pilot
ejected from the aircraft over Poland or East Germany.''
</TEXT>
