<FIRST>r a PM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0475 07-04 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Fire Destroys Homes; Fires Burn In N.M, Colo., Utah</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with 29 buildings burned, some
control gained overnight; PICKS UP 15th graf pvs, `A black ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACIENDA HEIGHTS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thousand firefighters today
battled a blaze roaring through canyons dotted with expensive homes.
The flames jumped from the brush to rooftops, burning 29 houses and
forcing out 500 people.
   The firefighters summoned from throughout Southern California
worked into a sweltering Independence Day to control the 1,500-acre
fire as it edged toward ridgetop homes in the Turnbull Canyon area
20 miles from downtown Los Angeles.
   Fires also burned Monday in eastern Utah, near Dinosaur National
Monument in northwestern Colorado and in New Mexico, where a
2,500-acre blaze near Diamond Peak in the Gila National Forest raged
out of control.
   The California fire began in an uninhabited, remote brushy area
and spread quickly to areas with homes valued at $300,000 to more
than $1 million.
   Firefighters hoped to surround the blaze by late today, said Los
Angeles County Fire Department Inspector Ken Sotro. Ten homes were
destroyed and 19 sustained major damage, and three firefighters
suffered minor injuries, he said.
   High humidity and relatively cool weather overnight helped
firefighters gain ground, Sotro said. But the Fourth of July
forecast for possibly high winds and temperatures over 100 degrees
worried firefighters after dawn.
   The fire was believed to have been caused by people, fire
Inspector John Lenihan said.
   ``Every little canyon is a finger of fire,'' he said, adding that
the terrain made the fire extremely difficult to surround.
   About 500 people arrived at Los Altos High School, which was
converted into an evacuation center. Most signed in to let
authorities know they escaped unharmed and then moved on to stay
with friends or at nearby motels.
   Some evacuees said the fire forced them out of their homes so
quickly they had to leave their possessions behind.
   ``They gave me five seconds _ I got nothing,'' said Joan Campbell.
   Sharon and Dick Hartman waited out the blaze near the fire
command post, sitting beside a van loaded with four caged birds, two
dogs and household items. ``What we grabbed were animals and
heirlooms, '' said Mrs. Hartman.
   The fire jumped through steep brush-filled canyons between the
ridgetop homes, Lenihan said.
   A black plume of smoke several thousand feet high could be seen
for at least 20 miles. Neighborhood streets were abandoned and
several residents turned on lawn sprinklers before fleeing. The few
roads to the area were closed.
   In Utah, crews worked to close lines around brush fires caused by
lightning. The fires scorched more than 635 acres in two Uintah
Basin forests and a third blaze broke out Monday in the upper
reaches of Uinta Canyon, 20 miles north of Roosevelt.
   The largest of several fires in Colorado, the Box Canyon Fire in
the northwest corner of the state, had spread by Monday to 1,520
acres of federal Bureau of Land Management property south of
Dinosaur National Monument.
   The fire was sparked by lightning Thursday and was declared near
containment at 190 acres early Sunday. But it erupted again and
reached 720 acres because of extremely dry conditions and rough
terrain.
   Fire danger was high across the state Monday.
   ``It's so dry, one firecracker will be enough,'' said Kris
Damsgaard of the U.S. Forest Service.
   A 2,500-acre blaze near Diamond Peak in the Gila National Forest
in New Mexico burned out of control. Firefighters managed to get a
2,840-acre fire southwest of Roswell under control Monday.
   Nearly 550 firefighters, along with five air tankers and eight
helicopters, battled the Divide fire, which straddles the
Continental Divide at the 9,000-foot level of Diamond Peak.
   ``It is burning out of control,'' said U.S. Forest Service
spokesman Ron Henderson. ``but if the winds lay down we can get a
hold of it within the next couple days. That's our biggest enemy
right now _ the wind.''
</TEXT>
