<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0506 07-04 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0506,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Enters Parliament in Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with speaker's election, government
resignation, quotes from Solidarity deputy. Pickup 10th graf, ``Jaruzelski
said ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent opposition entered an East
bloc legislature for the first time in more than four decades as
Solidarity and Communist-backed lawmakers today took a common oath
of office.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, head
of the Communist Party, watched the ceremony from seats near the
front of the Sejm, or parliament. It was broadcast live on state
television.
   ``We are starting the term of the Sejm, which may pass into
history as a great one. It can fulfill the expectations of our
society,'' said Zbigniew Rudnicki, the 60-year-old senior member of
the chamber who presided over the session.
   ``The eyes of 38 million Poles that live in the country are
directed to our changes. More lively still beat the hearts of Poles
all over the world from Chicago to Kazakhstan,'' he said.
   Rudnicki called on each deputy by name. They promised to work for
Poland's good in a oath that deleted a reference to its ``socialist
development.''
   Solidarity supporters claim 161 seats in the 460-member Sejm and
98 seats in a new 100-member Senate that was to meet later today.
   Electing a speaker was the first order of business and
sociologist Mikolaj Kozakiewicz of the Peasant Party met opposition,
although no other candidates ran. He was elected by 293 to 81, with
60 absentions.
   ``I will perform this function ... not bow before the mighty
rulers, ideologies or institutions,'' Kozakiewicz told the chamber.
Three vice marshals were elected from the Communist Party, the
Democratic Party and the opposition.
   Kozakiewicz recommended the chamber discuss a new government once
it elects a president. The president names a prime minister who
forms a government.
   Solidarity deputy Jacek Kuron harshly criticized the government
of Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, saying its ``chaotic
policy caused only social unrest.''
   There is an intense political struggle over who will be elected
in two days when the Sejm and Senate meet together.
   Jaruzelski said Friday he did not want the post and instead
recommended Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak. But Jaruzelski
was believed to be reconsidering this week at the urging of some
party members.
   The key issue appeared to be whether Jaruzelski would survive a
vote in the National Assembly, where the communist coalition holds
300 of 560 seats.
   Solidarity lawmakers have said they will vote against him, and it
is uncertain how many votes Jaruzelski can count on within his own
coalition.
   He acknowledged last week that he remains unpopular for imposing
martial law and crushing Solidarity, the East bloc's first
independent labor movement, in December 1981. The group was
re-legalized earlier this year.
   A leading opposition theorist proposed Monday that Solidarity
support a Communist candidate for president in exchange for a union
candidate taking the prime minister's office and forming the next
government.
   The proposal by Adam Michnik, a historian and essayist, in the
opposition's Election Gazette drew no immediate response from
authorities.
   The presidential election is timed to take place before President
Bush arrives in Poland on Sunday for a three-day visit.
   After Bush leaves, the legislators must choose a prime minister
and appoint the government to deal with skyrocketing inflation and
severe consumer shortages.
   The Polish legislature has not had such an opposition presence
since 1947, when the Commmunists consolidated power through
intimidation, forcing opposition leader Stanislaw Mikolayczyk into
exile.
   The new political arrangement stems from an agreement in April
between Communist authorities and the Solidarity-led opposition.
   That pact allowed the lifting of the seven-year ban on
Solidarity, provided for the country's freest elections of the
postwar period, and restored the Senate and presidency.
</TEXT>
