<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout with Bush call from Ghandi,
to Turks, other details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, spending a private
Independence Day with his family, received a call from Indian Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi this morning wishing him a happy holiday, the
White House said.
   Gandhi told him the Fourth of July is an important day for all
democracies and said the U.S. founding fathers had a great impact on
the Indian constitution, according to a news release issued by
Bush's staff at the vacationing White House in Maine.
   The president and Mrs. Bush pitched in to clean up debris from
the massive fireworks display over their home Monday night, the
White House said.
   Bush planned to spend most of the day at the family compound at
Walker's Point, playing tennis and boating. He also was reviewing
briefing materials for his upcoming trip to Europe, said press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   The president is preparing for his visit to Poland by staking out
a position likely to go over well there _ a call for the Soviet
Union to withdraw its troops from the East bloc nation.
   Bush, who leaves Sunday for a stop in Poland on his way to the
European economic summit, said the Soviets should pull out of Poland
and take ``an historic opportunity to help end the postwar division
in Europe.''
   On another matter, the White House said Bush called Turkish
Premier Turgut Ozal Monday to ``express his concern about the
maltreatment and forced expulsion of the Turkish ethnic minorities
from Bulgaria.''
   The statement gave no further details of the president's
conversation with Ozal, whose office announced the phone call Monday.
   Since he will be traveling next week, Bush on Monday called King
Hassan of Morocco to express his regards on the king's 60th
birthday, which falls during that time.
   Bush told the king the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff,
Admiral William Crowe, will represent the United States at the
King's birthday celebrations. Crowe announced on Sunday that he will
resign from the military in September and Bush told reporters he
wished Crowe had decided to stay on as chairman.
   The White House staff released a text Monday of Bush's interview
with a group of Polish reporters in which Bush made the proposal on
Soviet troops. The interview on Friday marked the first time he has
called for a total pullout.
   The news came on a day when Bush also issued a statement
applauding the Supreme Court's decision opening the door to more
restrictions on abortions.
   Bush said he welcomed the court's move to let states tackle the
issue of how they want to limit abortion. ``The court appears to
have begun to restore to the people the ability to protect the
unborn,'' he said.
   He called further for the reversal of the 1973 Roe vs. Wade
decision that legalized abortion, a ruling the court stopped short
of overturning Monday.
   Bush was on the golf course Monday when his staff released the
statement, and he told reporters with him he had ``very strong
feelings'' on the subject.
   Bush's chief of staff, John Sununu, told reporters Bush still
backs a constitutional amendment against abortion, and that he will
focus his attention on that rather than getting involved in state
legislative fights over abortion where he might be seen as meddling
in state affairs.
   Later Monday night, Bush got an early start on Independence Day
festivities by hosting a lavish fireworks show for neighbors, with
the explosions cascading over his family compound at Walker's Point.
   Bush had some 200 family and friends at the complex for the show,
which the White House said was funded by an anonymous donor.
   Bush told the Polish reporters he hopes to deliver his promised
economic incentives to Poland as a reward for its recent steps
toward democracy. But he said: ``We need to know that you're going
to be able to not only continue existing reforms, but expand on
reforms so that the economic system that works will be given a
chance to work unfettered.''
   Soviet troop withdrawal would be a good move, he said, because
``there is no danger at all of an invasion of Poland from the
West,'' and thus no need for large conventional forces.
   ``Very candidly, I would like to see Soviet troops ... out,''
Bush said
</TEXT>
