<FIRST>r a AM-MeterMutts     07-04 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meter Mutts,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pet Owners Protest Dog Blacklist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meter readers have been in the doghouse
since pet owners discovered the utility keeps a list of homes with
hostile hounds.
   To help employees avoid dog bites, the Green Bay Water Utility
has kept track of dangerous yards for almost 40 years. Two months
ago, the city began using the list to notify homes their dogs had to
be licensed.
   Some people who received the letters accused the utility's three
meter readers of spying.
   Utility office manager Keith Mueller said someone telephoned and
demanded: ``What's next? Are you going to watch to make sure I
control my noxious weeds?''
   Another caller declared: ``You're dead meat.''
   Someone mailed a water payment in an envelope addressed ``Dog
Catchers Inc.''
   About 200 of the people who got letters replied they did not own
dogs.
   Mueller said that when the mayor's office requested the list, the
utility was not immediately aware why. The list is programmed into
hand-held computers that meter readers consult before venturing onto
a property.
   Use of the list has paid off. Since notices were mailed at the
end of April, license fees received by the city this year went from
less than $5,400 to more than $19,500.
   Mueller said the complaints have tailed off, and he hopes it
stays that way.
   ``No pun intended, but let a sleeping dog lie,'' he said.
</TEXT>
