<FIRST>r a AM-SexNewsracks     07-04 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Newsracks,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Strikes Down Local Tabloid Restriction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city's attempt to regulate the location of
newsracks selling a non-obscene sex newspaper was struck down by a
state appeals court.
   The court rejected the city of Alameda's argument that The
Spectator was entitled to no more legal protection than adult
theaters or bookstores, which can be kept away from residential
areas and schools through zoning ordinances.
   Newsracks are not the same as adult bookstores and theaters,
Justice Donald King said in the 3-0 opinion Monday.
   ``There are no flashing lights or gaudy displays. There is no
steady stream of lingering customers. The product is not intended to
be consumed at the site of its purchase,'' King wrote.
   The judge said the city's restrictions were based solely on the
content of The Spectator, which has not been found obscene and is
thus protected by the First Amendment.
   ``They dared the courts to obliterate the First Amendment and
lost the gamble,'' said Amitai Schwartz, a lawyer for the tabloid.
   Chuck Corica, mayor of the city of 76,000, said the City Council
may appeal.
   ``There are very many mothers in Alameda concerned about this,''
he said. ``We are not attempting to skirt the First Amendment, not
saying you can't purchase The Spectator, just want to make it
difficult for small children to get hold of it.''
   Alameda's ordinance, which was never enforced, banned sales of
sexually oriented material in newsracks within 500 feet of
residential areas.
   Upholding a lower court, the appeals court said zoning
restrictions on sex-oriented bookstores and theaters are based on
the harm to the neighborhood.
   ``Neither prior cases, independent studies nor common sense have
yet demonstrated that adult newsracks downgrade neighborhoods,''
King said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
