<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Quake     07-04 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Quake,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderate Quake Hits Oshima</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake struck the island of Oshima
and nearby areas Tuesday night, but there were no reports of damage
or injury.
   The quake, which struck at 10:18 p.m. (9:18 a.m. EDT) and was
centered about six miles in the sea off the Izu peninsula, measured
4.9 on the Richter scale, according to the Central Meteorological
Agency.
   Oshima is 72 miles southwest of Tokyo.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6
severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage.
</TEXT>
