<DOCNO> AP890704-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     07-04 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Remains Elusive for Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Haughey couldn't win power
outright in an election and now he can't swallow the prospect of
sharing it with another party.
   So Ireland has been without a new government for nearly a week,
and the solution may hinge on a widely shared aversion to yet
another election.
   ``There'll be an election over my dead body,'' says Terry Leyden,
a lawmaker of Haughey's Fianna Fail party.
   Haughey was forced to resign last week after failing to win
re-election by Parliament as taoiseach, or prime minister.
   That left him with two choices: call another election, or form a
coalition with another party. He rejected both.
   The Dail, or Parliament, has given him until Thursday to produce
a government. Instead of overtures of compromise, however, public
positions have hardened.
   A front-page cartoon in The Irish Times on Tuesday showed Haughey
preparing to march under defiant banners: ``No Surrender'' and ``No
to Power Sharing.''
   Those, as every Irish citizen knows, are the slogans of Northern
Ireland's hard-line Protestants, who have no love for Haughey or his
Irish Republic.
   ``You cannot go on as if an election had never been held and
ignoring the reality. Nobody won the election,'' Jim Kemmy, the only
Democratic Socialist in the Dail, told Haughey on Monday.
   In the June 15 election, Fianna Fail's strength in the Dail fell
from 80 to 77 seats.
   Fine Gael gained four seats, for a total of 55, but its coalition
partners, the Progressive Democrats, fell from 14 to six.
   ``We recognize there is a totally changed situation,'' said
Haughey.
   Nonetheless, he has sought to recreate the pre-election
situation, when Fianna Fail ruled as a minority government with
support from Fine Gael and the Progressive Democrats.
   The old partners, however, demand new terms. ``It was clear to
anybody with any political sense that a new approach was needed,''
said Alan Dukes, Fine Gael's leader.
   Dukes offered Haughey a 50-50 share of cabinet seats in a
coalition. Desmond O'Malley, leader of the Progressive Democrats,
offered his party's six votes _ exactly the number needed _ in
return for Cabinet seats.
   ``Coalitions don't work,'' Haughey said.
   Although his party won only 44 percent of the popular vote and a
like proportion of the seats, Haughey claimed a mandate on the
grounds that Fianna Fail got the most votes.
   ``We are fulfilling the democratic wish of the people in seeking
to form a minority Fianna Fail government,'' Haughey said Sunday.
   Resistance to a coalition runs deep in Fianna Fail, which
conceives of itself more as a popular movement than a political
party.
   Noel Dempsey, a Fianna Fail deputy from Meath, said his
constituents disliked coalitions and ``they're prepared to go to the
country on the issue.''
   Since forming its first government in 1932, Fianna Fail has
dominated Irish politics, always winning between 42 to 52 percent of
the vote.
   The rivalry between Fianna Fail and Fine Gael is old as the civil
war that their founders fought on opposing sides in 1922-23.
   Strains between Fianna Fail and the Progressive Democrats,
however, are recent and personal. O'Malley was involved in two
attempts to remove Haughey as Fianna Fail leader and was finally
expelled from Fianna Fail in 1985, which makes it doubly irksome for
Haughey to have him at his Cabinet table.
   ``We are not in the business of recrimination, of settling old
scores of forcing others to eat their words or political humble
pie,'' O'Malley said in the Dail Monday.
   Paul McNulty, a Fianna Fail adviser, said a coalition wouldn't
work because the Progressive Democrats are a ``yuppie'' party while
Fianna Fail has ``its roots firmly planted in the less-privileged
sector of Irish society.''
   The Democrats, he added, lacked Fianna Fail's commitment, hardly
mentioned in the election campaign, to uniting the Irish Republic
and British-ruled Northern Ireland.
   Although it came second in the election, Fine Gael conceivably
could form a coalition with the Progressive Democrats and two
leftist Labor Party and Workers Party. But the left isn't dealing.
   Fianna Fail, Fine Gael and the Progressive Democrats won 138 of
the Dail's 166 seats, and Workers Party chairman Proinsias De Rossa,
said: ``It is up to them to sit down and implement that mandate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
