<FIRST>r w AM-Abortion-Congress     07-04 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Congress,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liberals in Congress Say Tide Will Turn on Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberal members of Congress concede there is
little support on Capitol Hill for legislation to roll back the new
Supreme Court decision on abortion.
   But they suggest the restrictions the court said states could
impose will in time spark such a strong public outcry that Congress
will enact bills counteracting the ruling.
   Jubilant conservatives, meanwhile, promised to press ahead with
efforts to further restrict abortions.
   Ruling in a Missouri case, the court said Monday that states may
refuse to allow tax dollars and public facilities to be used for
abortions and may require doctors to determine through various tests
whether a fetus at least 20 weeks old is capable of surviving
outside the womb.
   In that decision, the divided court chipped away at the
constitutional right to an abortion, a right it had spelled out in
the landmark Roe Vs. Wade case in 1973. And it scheduled three more
abortion cases for its fall term.
   ``Now we have to start the battle to keep that chipping process
from taking place,'' Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the
Energy and Commerce Health Subcommittee, said of liberal lawmakers'
next steps.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of the Judiciary
Subcommittee on Civil and Constitutional Rights, said he believed
support in both houses of Congress to overturn the court ruling was
lacking. But he predicted the decision would ``energize'' the
public, and consequently lawmakers.
   ``I predict we'll have a majority in both the House and Senate
for either a statute or constitutional amendment in a relatively
short time,'' he said. ``This is going to be a real national
battleground.''
   But he conceded that could take months or even years.
   Congress has been moving in the other direction in recent years,
in the face of politically active abortion opponents, approving
restrictions on the use of federal money for abortions.
   However, Edwards predicted congressional support for defending
abortion would swell gradually as women run into roadblocks to
ending pregnancies.
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., one of Congress' most stalwart abortion
foes, said he believed the court's ruling would make battles on
Capitol Hill even more vigorous. Abortion supporters, eyeing the
Supreme Court's ruling, would realize their only option is to pass
legislation, he said.
   ``We're in for a revived and renewed struggle over this issue for
some time,'' he said.
   Another anti-abortion activist, Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J.,
said Monday's ruling had led him to explore whether the court was
opening up avenues for new legislative restrictions.
   He said he and his allies are considering bills to bar federal
assistance to private groups that perform abortions or abortion
counseling, and to severely limit the legality of the procedure in
Washington, D.C., and the U.S. territories, where Congress has
direct legislative power.
   On the other side, Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., said she
would soon introduce legislation to increase federal research into
contraceptives, in part to use it to gauge support among her
colleagues for abortion. Public support, she agreed, would be
crucial.
   ``You're not going to have the votes until members start hearing
from the other side,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890704-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Baker     07-04 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says Increased Aid Needed to Help Philippine Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III told an
international gathering Tuesday that nations must pledge increased
aid to the Philippines to ensure the ``fragile'' young democracy
survives.
   The Philippines foreign secretary, Raul Manglapus, said it was
appropriate that the opening of the three-day session coincided with
the United States' Independence Day, and he called it ``a conclave
of democracy.''
   Delegates from more than a dozen countries and seven
international organizations are meeting to discuss the Philippines
Multilateral Aid Initiative, a plan aimed at protecting the key
Southeast Asian country.
   The purpose of the meeting, Baker said, ``is much more than
strengthening economic reform in one country. It is to express in
tangible ways our commitment to the success of democracy and
freedom.''
   ``Democracy in the Philippines remains fragile and under
attack,'' he told delegates.
   President Bush has asked Congress for an additional $200 million
in annual aid to help reach a goal of $10 billion in the next five
years for the Philippines, where the United States has six military
bases.
   The delegates praised economic and social reforms started since
Corazon Aquino became president of the Philippines in 1986 after the
ouster of Ferdinand Marcos, but they also heard of the difficulties
the country faces.
   Almost half of the Philippine people live under the
government-set poverty line, the foreign debt is $28 billion, and
communist rebels have been fighting for 20 years to topple the
government.
   Mrs. Aquino, speaking on a videotape shown to the conference,
said the Philippine people had ``succeeded against overwhelming
odds'' in restoring democratic institutions since Marcos' 20-year
rule ended.
   ``We now ask for your help in the more arduous task of protecting
and sustaining those gains by providing us the means to maintain a
viable and prosperous economy which can serve as a solid base for
social and political stability,'' she said.
   Japan, the source of about half the Philippines' bilateral aid,
said it was increasing its aid this year to about $1 billion from
$899 million last year.
   The European Community said its aid would roughly triple from the
recent annual average of $117 million to about $350 million.
   Baker, who arrived Tuesday for a 22-hour stopover, travels
Wednesday to Brunei to attend a meeting with foreign ministers of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations. Its members are
Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore, Indonesia, the Philippines and Brunei.
   Baker held separate meetings with Japanese Prime Minister Sousuke
Uno and Foreign Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka and discussed bilateral
trade problems and turmoil in China, Japanese and U.S. officials
said.
   Uno appears in an increasingly weak political position. His
governing party suffered a major setback in weekend voting for the
Tokyo city legislature, and he is plagued by allegations he kept
several paid mistresses.
   Baker, speaking to reporters during the 17-hour flight from
Washington, said it is important to ``studiously avoid involving
ourselves in the internal affairs of the government of Japan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
