<DOCNO> AP890704-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     07-04 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Lift Land Siege Around Christian Enclave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian-allied Moslem forces reopened
gateways linking the Christian enclave with the rest of Lebanon on
Tuesday, but Syrian gunners bombarded Christian ports to maintain
the sea blockade.
   Police said one person was killed and five wounded in pre-dawn
shelling duels across Beirut's dividing Green Line, bringing the
toll to 397 people killed and 1,538 wounded in the 16-week
confrontation between Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly Christian Lebanese
army troops and Syrian soldiers.
   Syrian gunners stopped their shelling 35 minutes before Moslem
forces lifted the land siege.
   Thousands of civilians flooded the three crossings, in Beirut,
north Lebanon and the mountains east of the capital, after they
reopened to traffic after almost four months.
   ``This is the first time in more than three months they allow me
to carry vegetables to east Beirut,'' said a woman at museum
gateway, her eyes brimming with tears.
   Moslem soldiers searched cars and frisked pedestrians for weapons.
   The Syrian-backed Moslem army command of Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, a
dissident Lebanese army officer, said private cars will be allowed
to cross into the 310-square-mile Christian enclave for 13 hours
during the day.
   Trucks carrying food and other commodities will be allowed to
cross at night, the statement said. It did not elaborate.
   A source at Aoun's command said the reopening was ``an
encouraging sign.''
   ``We'll wait to see if they allow supplies to cross overnight,''
the source said on condition of anonymity.
   The enclave, home to about 1 million Christians, has been under
siege by Syrian and allied forces since March 14.
   Shiite Moslem militia chieftain Nabih Berri, Syria's closest ally
in Lebanon, announced Monday the land siege would be lifted as ``a
goodwill gesture.''
   It appears to be a guarded response to an Iraqi offer Sunday to
stop supplying arms to Aoun if Syria withdraws from Lebanon. Iraq
and Syria are rivals for influence in the Arab world.
   Berri said Beirut airport also would be reopened Tuesday.
   But the airport police commander, Lt. Col. Ahmed Abu Zaki, said
this was delayed for ``technical reasons.'' Workers on Tuesday were
repairing the airport, closed March 12 after shells exploded on its
runway.
   Salim Salam, general manager of Middle East Airlines, said the
state airline is prepared to resume flights to Beirut airport in 48
hours. Lebanon's is the only airline that uses the airport.
   Aoun did not comment on Tuesday's reopening, decided after a
weekend meeting in Damascus of five Syrian-backed Moslem militia
leaders with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, Aoun's rival and head of the
Moslem Cabinet, said the move was ``a basic step toward resolving
the crisis.''
   Aoun had separate meetings with ambassadors of the United States,
Britain, France and the Soviet Union to complain about the sea
blockade Tuesday, the Christian Voice of Lebanon radio said.
   It said Aoun also sent cables to U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar and Arab League Secretary-General Chedli Klibi
about ``the interception by Syrian naval vessels of commercial ships
in Lebanese territorial waters.''
   The independent daily An-Nahar reported Tuesday that Syria has
tightened the blockade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
