<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd item to DELETE extraneous `thing' in lead.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dog's life isn't anything to complain
about around here.
   At the Yuppy Puppy in Coral Springs, a masseuse digs her fingers
into dogs. A health spa in Sunrise offers a bubbling Jacuzzi for the
family pet. And a groomer in moneyed Palm Springs dispatches
limousines to fetch lazy lap dogs.
   Toy poodle Korbel's third birthday present last month was the
full treatment at the Yuppy Puppy: an hour-long grooming session
followed by a massage, shampoo and whirlpool bath. The $60 session
wound up with wheat snacks and spring water from the French Alps.
   ``This is my child,'' said Iris Torres. ``He has the best life
there is. He's a spoiled brat.''
   Coral Springs also has an animal psychologist, while an animal
doctor in Vero Beach will cap the family mutt's unsightly teeth. In
Miami, a jeweler will pierce Fifi's ears.
   Shops in Fort Lauderdale and Coral Springs market such items as
Beverly Hills dog cologne at $6.95 a bottle and designer pet pajamas
for $13.95 a pair.
   Cats in need of a good drink after a tough day's lounging around
can knock back something called catnip liqueur, a non-alcoholic
beverage which sells for $8.50.
   Poodle Paradise in Palm Springs offers $150 mink and cashmere
coats. Diamond collars also are available for the discerning pooch.
   ``Why should they wear fakes when mom's wearing the real thing?''
asked owner Cory Russo.
</TEXT>
