<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Czars     07-04 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Czars,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Call on Gorbachev For Czarist Bond Repayment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While some capitalists are lining up to make money
in the Soviet Union, about 100 demonstrators rallied Tuesday during
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's visit to demand repayment on a
decades-old investment that didn't work out.
   Francois Bayle, vice president of an association of holders of
prerevolutionary Russian bonds, called on French leaders to press
Gorbachev to repay at least part of the lost money.
   ``Gorbachev Can Pay _ Gorbachev Should Pay,'' read one banner in
the crowd outside the Bourse, the Paris stock market.
   The association estimates that between 30,000 and 50,000 people
in France are holding bonds issued by Russia's czarist government.
The bonds are still listed on the stock exchange for about 75 cents
each, although since the 1917 revolution that brought the communists
to power there has been little prospect for repayment.
   Bayle said the association would accept repayment of a fraction
of the original face value of the bonds.
