<DOCNO> AP890704-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CorruptionTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0479 07-04 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Corruption Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0479,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Two `Incubator' Defendants Found Guilty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, `Raymond, a ...' with 2 grafs to ADD background
on New York City corruption.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former court clerk and a one-time top aide of
the late Mayor Harold Washington were convicted of accepting $80,000
from an FBI informant posing as a businessman trying to buy his way
into city contracts.
   A federal jury deliberated about 16 hours over four days before
returning the verdict Monday against the last two defendants caught
in the FBI's Operation Incubator probe into corruption at City Hall.
   Twnety-four other public officials already were convicted in the
investigation in Chicago and New York City.
   Morgan Finley, 63, who served as chief administrator of the Cook
County court until November, was convicted on charges of
racketeering conspiracy, attempted extortion and interstate travel
to aid a racketeering scheme.
   Clarence McClain, 47, who served the late mayor briefly but
remained a close friend after leaving Washington's administration,
was convicted on charges of racketeering conspiracy, attempted
extortion, interstate travel to aid a racketeering scheme, tax fraud
and mail fraud.
   ``The message here is that people who get paid off have to pay
the price,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Shepard, one of
three federal prosecutors in the case.
   Finley was acquitted on three of the nine counts against him in
the original indictment. McClain was acquitted on five of 16 counts
against him.
   U.S. District Judge Ilana Rovner set sentencing for July 25.
Finley faces a maximum of 105 years in prison and $1.5 million in
fines. McClain faces a maximum of 145 years and $2.5 million.
   ``We gave it our best shot,'' said McClain's attorney, Phil
Parenti, adding that no decision had been made yet on whether to
appeal.
   But Finley's attorney, Louis Garippo, said his client would
appeal, citing ``pretrial rulings limiting exploration of the
motives of (FBI informant) Michael Raymond.''
   Raymond, a convicted swindler, was the central figure in the
undercover investigation. Operation Incubator netted 16 convictions
in Chicago and spawned a probe in New York City that led to 10
convictions, including that of Stanley M. Friedman, Democratic
chairman of the Bronx.
   Friedman and four co-defendants were found guilty in a scheme to
get a $22.7 million Parking Violations Bureau contract for hand-held
computers through a pattern of racketeering. He was sentenced to 12
years in prison.
   Raymond became an informant after being arrested in July 1984 in
Tennessee on weapons charges. He agreed to pose in Chicago as a
businessman trying to bribe his way into lucrative city contracts
for collecting overdue parking fines and water bills.
   He often wined and dined politicians in a posh lakefront
apartment as FBI agents taped the proceedings from next door.
   When the investigation was disclosed in December 1985, some of
the politicians and allies of Washington contended it was an attempt
to embarrass his administration.
   Many others criticized the government's use of an unsavory
character like Raymond as an informant.
   But prosecutor Ira Raphaelson defended the use of Raymond as ``a
method of getting behind the closed door where most public
corruption takes place.
   ``We did not use him as a witness,'' he added. ``We used him as a
microphone.''
</TEXT>
