<FIRST>r i AM-Kadar     07-04 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kadar,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condition of Former Hungarian Leader Worsens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of former Communist Party
leader Janos Kadar has worsened, Hungarian radio said Tuesday, and
he was listed in critical condition at a Budapest hospital.
   Kadar, 77, was hospitalized Monday with pneumonia and severe
breathing and circulatory problems.
   He was visited Tuesday by party Chairman Reszo Nyers and party
General Secretary Karoly Grosz.
   Hospital sources said Kadar's wife, Maria, was constantly at her
husband's bedside.
   Hungarian radio gave no details of Kadar's condition. Other
state-run media ran only the same terse report.
   Kadar was stripped of his last Communist Party posts in May after
he was reported gravely ill.
   The party leader for 32 years, Kadar had been named honorary
party chairman in May 1988, when Grosz became general secretary. In
the past year, Kadar's political legacy has come increasingly into
question.
   After guiding Hungary to relative prosperity and tolerance by the
1970s, he was seen as an obstacle to political and economic reform
in the 1980s.
   He has not been seen in public since April, when participants at
a communist Central Committee meeting said he gave a long, rambling
speech.
   In recent interviews, Kadar was quoted as saying the fate of Imre
Nagy and other leaders of the 1956 Hungarian revolt was his
``personal tragedy.''
   Kadar came to power after Soviet troops and tanks crushed the
uprising, and Nagy and his associates were executed on charges of
high treason in 1958 after a Stalinist show trial.
   Nagy and other uprising leaders were honored as national martyrs
at a ceremony June 16 after what amounted to a political
rehabilitation of Nagy and a re-evaluation of the uprising.
</TEXT>
