<DOCNO> AP890704-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Korea     07-04 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Protest Travel Bans to North Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea-Fourth, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students fought
riot police with rocks and firebombs Tuesday during rallies to
support a Seoul student who defied the government and attended a
youth festival in North Korea.
   Media reports Tuesday said national security agents plan to
question opposition leaders in connection with another unauthorized
trip to North Korea by a National Assembly member.
   The legislator, Suh Kyung-won of the main opposition Party for
Peace and Democracy, surrendered June 25, and authorities say he
will be charged with espionage in connection with the trip last year.
   South Korea forbids unauthorized trips to the communist nation
and says contact between the countries must be through official
channels.
   The visit by Suh has been of special concern to authorities
because he is a national legislator and because he and officials in
Pyongyang kept the trip secret for 10 months.
   Radical students opposed to the travel law yelled ``Abolish
national security laws!'' and ``Miss Im Suk-yong, you are brave and
wonderful!'' as they battled police at Seoul's Yonsei University.
The clash lasted more than an hour before students were dispersed by
police firing tear gas.
   Im Suk-young, a senior at Seoul's Hankuk University of Foreign
Studies, went to Pyongyang for the 13th World Festival of Youth and
Students, which ends Saturday.
   The government has said she will be arrested and charged with
national security violations when she returns.
   In the provincial city of Kwangju, about 500 students fought riot
police with rocks and firebombs at Chosun University, according to
Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   Yonhap said police used tear gas to disperse students who then
regrouped and staged street demonstrations in the downtown section.
   The radical National Council of Student Representatives announced
it had drafted an inter-Korea student communique that calls for a
``drastic reduction'' of military forces in North and South Korea
and the gradual withdrawal of U.S. troops and nuclear weapons from
the peninsula.
   Im Chong-suk, chairman of the organization, told a news
conference the draft was being sent to the North for approval and
signing by Miss Im.
   There are an estimated 1 million troops in North Korea and about
650,000 in South Korea. An additional 43,000 U.S. troops are
stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Radical students, a small but vocal minority, say the U.S. troops
hinder reunification.
   Intelligence agents are investigating how Miss Im obtained a
passport and money for her trip and whether there is any connection
with her trip and that of Suh or the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, who is on
trial for an unauthorized trip to North Korea in April.
   Moon is the brother of opposition legislator Moon Tong-hwan, who
reportedly faced questioning in connection with Suh's visit to North
Korea in August, 1988, during which he met with North Korean
President Kim Il Sung.
   The daily newspaper Dong-A Ilbo said authorities want to find out
if Moon helped plan Suh's trip.
   Eight other people have been arrested in Suh's case, mostly for
failing to report his trip to authorities. The crime is punishable
by a $3,000 fine and up to five years in prison.
</TEXT>
