<FIRST>r i AM-China-HongKong     07-04 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Says China Must Restore Confidence Among Hong Kong Residents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China must take ``a whole series of actions'' to
restore confidence among Hong Kong residents after its brutal
crackdown on the pro-democracy movement, Britain's foreign secretary
said Tuesday.
   ``I don't begin to say that there's any single action that any
Chinese leader could take that could wipe the slate clean or
anything like that,'' Sir Geoffrey Howe declared. ``It's going to be
a long business.''
   He urged the United States and other nations not to impose
further economic sanctions on China. Howe said that would seriously
damage the colony, which Britain has agreed to return to China in
1997.
   Howe commented at the end of a three-day visit, during which he
was criticized for Britain's refusal to grant the right of residence
in Britain to the colony's 5.7 million people.
   About 6,000 citizens marched through downtown Hong Kong to mark
one month since the army assault the night of June 3-4 on Tienanmen
Square, which was occupied by student demonstrators. They shouted:
``Down with communism! Down with the Communist Party!''
   Li Peng, the Chinese premier who ordered the crackdown, was
portrayed on posters as Dracula and Howe as a bumbling panda.
   Howe stood by the 1984 agreement, under which Britain agreed to
return the colony and China promised continued capitalism and a
``high degree of autonomy'' in Hong Kong under a ``one country, two
systems'' policy.
   On Tuesday, the foreign secretary said there was a ``huge gap of
broken confidence to be overcome.''
   Trust can be restored, he said, only by ``a whole series of
actions, rather than words'' from Beijing. Howe said Hong Kong
residents will watch closely how China treats its own people and
drafts a constitution for the territory.
   The depth of the confidence crisis was indicated by a poll
released Tuesday in which 54 percent of 1,000 residents questioned
expressed pessimism about the future.
   Results of the poll by Survey Research Hong Kong, conducted in
the last week of June, indicated slightly more than half the people
may emigrate. The figure rose to nearly two-thirds for professionals
and executives.
   Howe said, without giving details, that Britain would allow a
select group of Hong Kong residents to emigrate to Britain, speed
democratic reform and seek international support for the territory's
people.
   He said other countries could help the colony, which has
extensive economic links with China, by not imposing further
economic sanctions.
   ``Hong Kong would be gravely damaged if the United States, still
yet other countries, were to engage in economic sanctions,'' he said.
   The foreign secretary said he was certain the most secure way of
being able ``to re-establish contact of a sensible kind, with a
sensible leadership'' in Beijing was to retain the prospect of
economic relations with each other.
</TEXT>
