<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-04 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Accuses Foreign Intelligence Agencies of Subversion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa on
Tuesday accused unspecified foreign intelligence agencies of
whipping up disturbances to try to subjugate Sri Lanka.
   ``They hire people from inside the administration and work
insidiously through them to wreck the administration,'' Premadasa
told a rally at Mahiyangana, 70 miles northeast of Colombo.
   ``In the past when a country wanted to conquer another it waged a
war. But today when a country wants to tame, suppress or enslave
another country, it resorts to different methods,'' he said,
according to a text released by the government.
   Premadasa did not identify the foreign agencies but appeared to
be referring to his country's northwestern neighbor, India.
   ``You know what happened in the north and east of Sri Lanka. From
where did our people get that help to attack our own people?'' he
asked.
   Sri Lanka had accused India of aiding and training rebels of the
Tamil minority who have been fighting for six years for an
independent nation. At least 9,000 people have been killed in the
rebellion, mostly dominant Sinhalese.
   India has denied the charges and in 1987 sponsored a peace accord
aimed at giving Tamils local autonomy.
   Under the plan, India deployed peacekeeping troops to supervise a
rebel surrender. But the soldiers soon became involved in a
guerrilla war with the dominant Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
who reneged on the accord.
   Premadasa began peace talks with the Tamil Tigers in May and
asked India to withdraw its estimated 45,000 troops by July 29, the
second anniversary of the accord.
   But India rejected the request, saying a hasty withdrawal could
lead to even greater ethnic violence. The refusal has angered the
Sri Lankan government and opposition parties.
   Samuel Bandaranaike, president of the Sri Lanka Patriotic United
Progressive Front, suggested Colombo break diplomatic ties with New
Delhi.
   ``If India is not respecting the sovereignty and territorial
integrity of Sri Lanka, then our front will be compelled to agitate
to sever diplomatic relations immediately,'' he said in an interview.
   Bandaranaike's powerful coalition is believed to be close to the
People's Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese group bitterly
opposed to the Indian troop presence.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi said he is willing to
negotiate a timetable for a troop withdrawal with Sri Lankan
officials.
   Sinhalese extremists killed seven policemen Tuesday in three
separate attacks in the south of this island nation, a police
official said. The government blames the militants for at least
3,500 killings in two years.
   The extremists in 1987 launched a violent campaign against the
government, which they accuse of making too many concessions to the
Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   Tamils say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who
comprise 75 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
