<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills Colombian State Governor, Five Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with 6 killed, bomb in parked car, police
suspect drug traffickers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in a parked car Tuesday
as a state governor's limousine passed by, killing him and five
other people, police said. The interior minister said he suspected
drug traffickers in the attack.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the bombing in
the headquarters of Colombia's cocaine cartel, the latest in scores
of attacks on government officials in the last five years.
   A parked car packed with dynamite blew up as Gov. Antonio Roldan
Betancur's bullet-proof car passed it near a sports stadium,
authorities said.
   Police said Roldan, governor of the state of Antioquia, was
killed as were two of his bodyguards, two pedestrians and a
councilman from the town of Itagui, who was passing by in another
car.
   Another bodyguard was hospitalized in critical condition, police
said in a statement.
   Interior Minister Raul Orejuela Bueno said in Bogota that he
suspected drug traffickers because they used a car bomb to try to
kill a senior security official a month ago in Bogota.
   That car bombing was an attempt to kill Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez,
the chief of Colombia's Administrative Security Department, the
security force in charge of national investigations.
   Seven persons were killed by that car bomb on May 30. Miguel Maza
was slightly injured.
   Medellin, a city of 2 million people, is the headquarters for
Colombia's biggest cocaine traffickers, who in the last five years
have killed an attorney general, a justice minister, 30 judges, two
newspaper editors and scores of policemen and other members of
government security forces.
   Before assuming office, Roldan was president of the Medillin
soccer team, Atletico Nacional, which was reportedly backed by drug
money.
