<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-04 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Says Guerrillas Planning Offensive on Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tanks and armored personnel carriers
roared through Kabul on Tuesday as the Afghan government said
guerrillas were planning a new offensive.
   The government called on the United Nations to stop the
``impending bloodbath.''
   The military vehicles moved at dawn in the Afghan capitial, and
witnesses said they saw soldiers digging in new positions in its
outskirts.
   In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar,
Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil said the guerrillas were being aided in
their planned attack by U.S. and Pakistani army generals. He did not
elaborate.
   There was no immediate comment on the government's claims from
the Moslem guerillas based in Pakistan. There was no comment in
Washington because of the Independence Day holiday.
   ``In such dangerous situation that we are facing aggression and
intervention from abroad we have to make necessary arrangements to
repulse and defend our country,''' said the letter, the text of
which was released to reporters.
   Wakil said the guerrillas plan to launch their attacks in
mid-July. He said he got his information from Afghan intelliegence
sources.
   ``The grave consequences, which will include bloodshed, killings
and destruction, will be shouldered by the Pakistani militarists and
overseas designers of the attack,'' the letter said.
   Foreign military analysts said a conventional attack on Kabul, a
city of 2.25 million, was unlikely, but they did not rule out
attempts by the insurgents to mount large scale guerrilla attacks on
Kabul and other major cities.
   The U.S.- and Pakistani-supported Moslem guerrillas have been
battling for more than a decade to overthrow the pro-Soviet
government in Kabul.
   Wakil said Perez de Cuellar should inform the members of the U.N.
Security Council of the situation.
   ``It is quite serious, we are making necessary arrangements but
we would like the world to know of the plans of the opponents,''
said Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani. ``It is a new
onslaught against the republic of Afghanistan, but we are determined
to defend our homeland.''
   Marxists seized power in a coup in April 1978, and Soviet troops
intervened to support them in Deceber 1979.
   The Soviets completed their troop withdrawal from Afghanistan on
Feb. 15 Under a U.N.-sponsored agreement to bring peace in
Afghanistan.
