<FIRST>u w PM-BlackCatholics 2ndLd-Writethru a0553 07-04 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Catholics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0553,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Mulls Suspending Priest Who Starts Black Church</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS lead with 1 graf and SUBS 6th graf pvs bgng, `Stallings
said,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Stallings reax, edit for transition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEROY TILLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest who set up an unauthorized church for
black parishioners has been suspended by the Roman Catholic
archbishop of Washington, a church spokeswoman said today, but the
priest said he would continue to hold unauthorized services.
   Cardinal James A. Hickey suspended the Rev. George A. Stallings
Jr. after the priest celebrated an unsanctioned worship ceremony at
the District of Columbia's Law School chapel last Sunday, said
spokeswoman Eileen Marks.
   Stallings, who was notified of Hickey's decision by registered
letter on Monday, is forbidden to preach, celebrate Mass or any of
the Catholic Church's sacraments including baptism, weddings and
Holy Communion, Marks said.
   The cardinal was leaving channels open for any possible dialogue
with Stallings despite the suspension, she said. Hickey's letter
said the decision was made in part to help Stallings turn away from
a course of action that the cardinal said was ``destructive.''
   The letter called the service Stallings performed at his newly
created Imani Temple last Sunday ``a public act of disobedience,''
and said the establishment of the separate group was ``a step
towards separating yourself from the unity of the Catholic church,''
Marks said.
   But Stallings responded today: ``The cardinal has failed to deal
with racism in the Catholic Church and hasn't responded to issues I
have brought to his attention.''
   In an interview with radio station WHUR-FM at the private,
predominantly black Howard University in Washington, Stallings said
he will hold services every Sunday at the Imani Temple, now located
at Suitland High School in Suitland, Md.
   ``The suspension only affects my duties with the Roman Catholic
Church,'' he said.
   Stallings had said earlier that he created the new congregation
because the Roman Catholic Church is not responsive to the cultural
and spiritual needs of black parishioners.
   Sunday's ceremony was attended by about 500 people and included
traditional Catholic prayers and liturgy, along with elements
borrowed from African and Southern black revival traditions. Black
representatives of other faiths, including Baptists and Muslims,
attended to show support for Stallings' move.
   Stallings, who has been on a collision course with church
officials since announcing his separate parish last month, said
Sunday, ``The church can't throw me out, and even if they do throw
me out, I have my own opinion ... they have theirs.''
   Efforts to reach Stallings by telephone for comment were
unsuccessful.
   Church officials said they oppose Stallings' methods but not his
efforts to respond to the black community.
   ``This situation has more to do with the needs and expectations
of Father Stallings than with broader questions about the adequacy
of Catholic ministry within the black community,'' Hickey said.
   ``As Catholics, we look to the bishop for overall guidance on
when to establish a new parish,'' said the Rev. William Lori,
secretary to Hickey. ``We can't have a priest setting up a new
parish and saying, `Hey, we have a better product over here.'''
</TEXT>
