<FIRST>u i AM-Solzhenitsyn     07-04 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solzhenitsyn,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writers' Union Votes to Restore Solzhenitsyn's Membership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Writers' Union has voted to reinstate
Alexander Solzhenitsyn, the chronicler of Stalinist terror who was
kicked out of the organization in 1969 and exiled five years later,
a newspaper reported Tuesday.
   Solzhenitsyn's rehabilitation will continue within a few days
when Novy Mir, the union's main journal, releases its July issue
containing the lecture he wrote after winning the Nobel Prize for
Literature in 1970, an editor at the journal said.
   Solzhenitsyn was barred from traveling to Sweden to deliver the
lecture and it has not been published in the Soviet Union.
   Next month, Novy Mir will publish three chapters of
Solzhenitsyn's monumental history of the Soviet labor camp system,
``The Gulag Archipelago,'' said Vadim Borisov, the editor who
prepared the text for publication. Another literary journal in
Estonia also is planning to publish parts of the book.
   Despite the gradual rehabilitation of Solzhenitsyn, the Soviet
government, which forcibly exiled him to the West in 1974, has yet
to restore his citizenship. The writers' union urged the government
to take that step, according to Literaturnaya Gazeta, the weekly
newspaper of the union.
   The exile lives with his family in seclusion in Cavendish, Vt.
   Literaturnaya Gazeta reported Tuesday the 26-member secretariat
of the writers' union had voted to revoke its ``wrongful'' expulsion
of Solzhenitsyn on Dec. 5, 1969.
   Two members of the ruling Politburo, Vadim A. Medvedev and
Alexandra P. Biryukova, have opposed publication of Solzhenitsyn's
works, and it was not clear when he might be fully exonerated.
   ``The Gulag Archipelago'' chronicles life in Soviet labor camps.
Solzhenitsyn was freed from the camps after Josef Stalin's death in
1953.
   A literary journal in the Baltic republic of Estonia, also is
publishing three chapters of ``The Gulag Archipelago'' in its sixth
issue, to appear shortly, said an editor of the journal in Tallinn.
   The journal, Looming, has a circulation of 32,000, and is
publishing the excerpts in Estonian, a language little spoken
outside the tiny republic.
   The complete version of the book is being translated into
Estonian and is expected to be published by EestiRaanat publishers,
said the Looming editor. She said the publication was authorized by
Solzhenitsyn himself, and was not cleared by any Soviet authorities.
   Borisov, an editor in the prose section of Novy Mir, said ``The
Gulag Archipelago'' excerpts slated for publication in that journal
had not been censored by Soviet authorities, although he
acknowledged that discussion over which parts to use had been going
on ``for several years.''
   ``We don't have to go to anyone before we publish, but the
journal has to be taken to Glavlit for approval,'' he said. Glavlit,
the state agency which makes sure that state secrets are not
published, formerly played a much more agressive censorship role.
   Borisov said material selected for publication included portions
on Vladimir Lenin, the founder of the Soviet state. Western editions
of ``The Gulag Archipelago'' say that Lenin started official
terrorism in the Soviet Union, still a controversial contention in
this country.
   Borisov said that Novy Mir would publish about one third of the
whole book. He said that Solzhenitsyn had refused to accept any
payment from Novy Mir for the publication.
   The article in Literaturnaya Gazeta did not mention when the
writers' union took its action, although union sources said the
decision was made at a meeting Friday.
   The works of Solzhenitsyn have not been published in his homeland
since Novy Mir carried his short novel ``One Day in the Life of Ivan
Denisovich'' in November 1962 during the cultural thaw under Nikita
S. Khrushchev. The thaw ended shortly thereafter, and Solzhenitsyn's
works were banned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
