<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     07-04 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Finishes Hearing Testimony in Palme Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of killing Prime
Minister Olof Palme refused to answer questions in court Tuesday,
ending testimony in the murder trial.
   ``It doesn't matter what I respond to your questions, so I will
not answer your questions,'' defendant Christer Pettersson told the
prosecutor.
   Pettersson, 42, repeated his denial that he killed Palme, the
socialist who dominated Swedish politics for more than a decade.
Palme was shot Feb. 28, 1986 while walking home from a movie in
downtown Stockholm with his wife, Lisbeth.
   The court cannot force a defendant to testify, so it adjourned
until Thursday.
   Then, Chief Prosecutor Anders Helin will sum up the case against
Pettersson, which relies heavily on the evidence of Mrs. Palme.
   Court officials said they will hear the defense summary Monday,
then retire to decide on a verdict, expected before the end of the
month.
   Mrs. Palme identified Pettersson as the man she saw just after
her husband fell to the street with a fatal bullet wound, though she
said she did not see him holding a gun.
   Pettersson, who has served a jail sentence for manslaughter and
is a known alcohol and drug abuser, also was seen in the area by
other witnesses who testified earlier in the monthlong trial.
   On Tuesday, the defense called an insurance company employee to
testify that Mrs. Palme appeared distraught and shocked immediately
after the shooting, implying her identification of Pettersson was
unreliable.
   Stig Engstrom, one of the first to rush over to Palme, appeared
to contradict Mrs. Palme's claim that she was collected enough to
remember seeing Pettersson, who she said was standing about five
yards away.
   Engstrom said Mrs. Palme was ``confused and disoriented.''
   Pettersson, who was arrested Dec. 14 after a three-year manhunt,
interrupted Helin when the prosecutor was about to question him for
the first time since the trial opened June 5.
   He denounced Helin's attempt to discredit defense witness Algot
Asell, who backed Pettersson's alibi that he was at a train station
17 miles outside Stockholm at the time of the shooting.
   ``I only have one witness on my side, whom you have done
everything to cast doubt on,'' he said. ``Imagine if you did an
investigation of every witness the way you did of the witness who
speaks in my favor.''
   Algot said he saw Pettersson at the station around the time of
the shooting, but he was unclear about the timing of his own
movements. Helin called Algot's estranged daughter to testify her
father's word was not to be trusted.
   As exhibits, the prosecutor has introduced a booklet and letter
found in Pettersson's home and described as containing anti-Palme
remarks.
   The letter was written to a friend on trial who was denied
permission to change his defense lawyer. Pettersson said in the
letter ``that's the way it goes in Palme's government.''
   The prosecution has tried to show Pettersson had a deep hatred of
all authority. Pettersson says he admired Palme personally.
</TEXT>
