<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh 1stLd-Writethru a0541 07-04 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike by 1{ Million Workers Closes Factories, Docks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with nearly all industrial workers striking;
30 injured in clashes with police; docks paralyzed. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly all of Bangladesh's 1.5 million
unionized industrial workers went on strike for higher wages
Tuesday, shutting down factories and docks, and emptying streets of
traffic, union leaders said.
   Strikers in Dhaka, the capital, damaged 10 vehicles and at least
30 strikers were injured in clashes with police, said Abdul
Mutallib, president of the Bangladesh Workers' Federation.
   In Mymensingh, 70 miles north of Dhaka, workers blocked rail
tracks and halted train traffic, said government official Nurul Huq.
   More than 20 trade unions backed by opposition political parties
joined in calling the 24-hour general strike. The unions represent
Bandladesh's 1.5 million industrial and railroad workers and demand
the government nearly double the minimum wage from the equivalent of
$25 a month to $44. They also want allowances pegged to the cost of
living and set at 60 percent of their wages.
   Most industrial workers are employed at textile, jute and carpet
manufacturing mills and factories.
   United News of Bangladesh news agency reported the strike
severely disrupted train, bus and ferry services all over the
country.
   Trade union leaders in Chittagong and Khulna ports, contacted by
telephone, said striking dock workers formed picket lines and halted
work there.
   In Dhaka, a normally bustling city of 4 million people, buses
stayed off the road and motorists did not venture out for fear of
violence.
   But the city's bicycle-rickshaws were out in force, transporting
commuters to offices. Rickshaws were exempted from the strike.
   Police officials said more than 200 youths were taken into
custody Monday night and early Tuesday. ``The boys have been picked
up on suspicion that they may carry out violence,'' a police
official said. ``They will be released after the strike is over.''
</TEXT>
