<DOCNO> AP890704-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Scene     07-04 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Scene,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Political Prisoners Given Run of the Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR50</HEAD>
<UNK>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young guard stopped the man with the
tousled hair and old blue jeans and asked for identification.
   But a superior quickly intervened, saying: ``Come in, Mr. Deputy.
No need for that.''
   That's how Adam Michnik, one of the country's most frequently
jailed dissidents, took his seat Tuesday in the Sejm among communist
deputies in the first East bloc legislature since the late 1940s to
have a real opposition.
   In a day redolent with ironies, 259 Solidarity-backed senators
and deputies sat down beside 300 communist coalition members, all
swearing the same oath ``to do everything for the well-being of the
motherland and the good of the citizens.''
   Gone was the reference contained in the old oath to do everything
``for the successful socialist development of the Polish People's
Republic.'' It had been agreed before the meeting that the
Solidarity representatives could not swear to uphold socialism.
   During the opening session of the Senate, Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa sat next to Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, the man
who signed the martial-law order to crush Walesa's independent union
in 1981.
   They seemed to get on famously.
   In the dining room of the Sejm, Solidarity lawmakers broke bread
with members of the communist coalition. In the corridors, Walesa's
driver bantered with uniformed Sejm guards.
   Less than a year ago, Jerzy Urban, then the government spokesman,
said negotiations could not begin with Solidarity until Walesa
dropped the radicals Michnik and Jacek Kuron from his negotiating
team.
   On Tuesday, Michnik and Kuron were among the first to speak.
Kuron launched into a sharp attack on the economic performance of
the government of Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski. Shortly
after he finished, Rakowski left the building and Kuron remained
behind.
   ``It feels strange,'' said Solidarity Deputy Jan Litynski,
another veteran activist, after the session.
   Asked why, he referred to the the fact that legislators cannot be
prosecuted under Poland's constitution.
   ``At one point after I had been sworn in and Henryk (Wujec) had
not, he said to me, `Now you can't be arrested and I still can,'''
Litynski said with a laugh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
