<DOCNO> AP890704-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FlagMan     07-04 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Man,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>`It's Us,' Vet Says of the Flag</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-July Fourth Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World War II veteran John Grillo spent
the Fourth of July as he does every other day: in the company of
hundreds of American flags.
   Grillo, 78, collects and sells all kinds of flags from the
business he runs out of his home. But it was Old Glory he reveled in
Tuesday.
   ``My goodness, I think I have about 200 or 300; more than that,
if you count the grosses and grosses of 4-by-6-inch and 6-by-9-inch
flags,'' said Grillo.
   In honor of the holiday, he hung 24 flags in front of his home,
two in his garden and another across the street.
   ``As they ride by, they'll see it,'' said Grillo, although he
conceded that not too many people were driving through his quiet
section of Mount Vernon, just north of New York City, over the
holiday.
   Grillo, who did clerical work with the 8th Air Force in England
during World War II, sells flags to clubs, municipalities and
ordinary citizens _ offering veterans an extra-good deal.
   Although business picks up over the Fourth, he generally has a
hard time making ends meet.
   ``In the U.S., there must be 15 or 20 major manufacturers and a
fewer small ones. They don't gross in sales what a toy or doll
company would,'' said Grillo.
   ``But it doesn't make me bitter,'' he added. ``This is a work of
love.''
   The flag is ``our signature,'' he said. ``It's everything we came
from _ blood, sweat and tears. It reminds us of mother and dad and
our ancestors. It's a beacon that lights the night; darkness has
never put it out. It's wholesome and good and clean _ it's us.''
   When he thinks about the Supreme Court allowing the desecration
of the flag, he gets so mad he can barely get out the words.
   ``They should send these characters on their way and have them
blow their noses,'' he says _ although it's not clear whether he
means flag-burners or the Supreme Court justices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
