<DOCNO> AP890704-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     07-04 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cohen Finds de Klerk `Reasonable,' Promises Changes in U.S. Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herman Cohen, the new assistant U.S.
secretary of state for African affairs, said Tuesday he finds the
man designated to be South Africa's next ruler to be a ``very
reasonable person.''
   Cohen met for an hour with National Party leader F.W. de Klerk
before flying to Namibia and the Ivory Coast on his first African
tour since he succeeded Chester Crocker.
   He said he could not outline the Bush administration's policy
toward South Africa because it won't be formalized until September.
   ``I believe there will be significant differences (from the
Reagan administration) in our new policy,'' Cohen said.
   It ``does have new emphasis and the new emphasis is on helping
the non-white community to improve its conditions and its political
leverage for the inevitable negotiations which will take place.''
   Cohen said he was ``particularly impressed'' by de Klerk's
``desire to continue regional cooperation, regional detente. I was
very happy to hear that he would like to continue and expand on his
program for greater economic involvement with neighboring
countries.''
   The main reason for his Africa trip is to attend a monitoring
commission of the U.S.-brokered peace accord between Angola, Cuba
and South Africa.
   Cohen intends to return to South Africa July 10 to continue
discussions with a broad range of leaders, from conservatives to
banned black nationalists.
   In London, British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Tuesday
she detects change in South Africa, but added she could not say when
black nationalist leader Nelson Mandela will be freed.
   ``I cannot tell when it (Mandela's freedom) will come about, but
I do believe that there is a change in South Africa,'' Mrs. Thatcher
told the House of Commons in answer to a legislator's question.
   She said Mandela has to be released before blacks and whites can
hold constitutional talks.
   Mandela was sentenced to life imprisonment in 1964 when he was
convicted of plotting to overthrow the government.
   Mrs. Thatcher said she hoped for ``movement toward negotiations''
after September general elections when South Africa's whites,
mixed-race and Indian voters will elect lawmakers of their racial
groups to the three segregated houses of Parliament. The black
majority has no vote.
   Also on Tuesday, attorney Clive Plasket said 128 blacks arrested
after a riot were released Tuesday and eight are being held in
connection with fighting that killed 11 people.
   The violence broke out Saturday when Bophuthatswana police broke
up what they called an illegal gathering at Leeuwfontein village,
150 miles northwest of Johannesburg. The meeting was to plan
strategy to stop the village being incorporated into Bophuthatswana,
a tribal homeland which South Africa calls an independent republic.
   Two civilians were killed when police fired at the crowd. Four
policemen were killed when a gasoline bomb hit their vehicle, and
five other officers were axed and stoned to death.
   Plasket said he saw the eight detainees, who have not been
charged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
