<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0602 07-04 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0602,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilotless Soviet Jet Fighter Crashes in Belgium</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to raise reference to ejection over Poland.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BRU2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet jet fighter flew over three
NATO nations Tuesday _ after its pilot ejected over Poland _ and
crashed into a house near the French-Belgian border, killing an
18-year-old man inside.
   Officials of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization said U.S.
F-15s intercepted the MiG-23 soon after it entered NATO airspace and
accompanied it until it crashed. They said the Soviet plane was not
armed.
   The Soviet news agency Tass said the plane went astray after the
pilot ejected because of equipment failure ``during a training
flight over Poland.'' It said the pilot survived.
   Tass said the Soviet Defense Ministry was ``contacting
governments of the countries whose airspace was crossed by the
plane.'' The nations were West Germany, the Netherlands and Belgium.
   In Brussels, Foreign Minister Mark Eyskens summoned the Soviet
ambassador to his office for further explanations, a spokesman for
Eyskens said.
   At the Defense Department in Washington, Air Force Maj. Mike
Stepp said the NATO air defense system picked up the MiG ``before it
ever crossed into NATO airspace,'' and the F-15s ``were scrambled
and intercepted the aircraft.''
   When the American pilots caught the Soviet plane, they saw ``it
had no canopy and no pilot,'' he said.
   West German government sources said in Bonn that Soviet officials
apparently gave NATO no warning that the plane was approaching, and
one questioned why Warsaw Pact defenses did not try to shoot it down.
   ``We would like to know whether the Soviets knew an aircraft was
about to go West and why they never made any attempt to bring it
down in their airspace,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The plane flew over some of Western Europe's most densely
populated areas and went down only miles from a cluster of urban
areas along the border.
   Gaston Bourlet of the Belgian Defense Ministry said the MiG
crashed at 10:37 a.m. (4:37 a.m. EDT) into a house near Wevelgem, 50
miles west of Brussels, killing the young man.
   Firefighters fought the flames for more than an hour.
   Military officials in West Germany, the Netherlands and Belgium
said the MiG-23 arrived over West Germany at 9:42 a.m. and there was
no response to radio requests for identification. The U.S. Air Force
F-15s scrambled from Soesterberg Air Force base in the central
Netherlands and caught the intruder over northern West Germany.
   After crossing into northern Holland at 40,000 feet, the Soviet
fighter veered southward, lost speed and altitude, and crashed 55
minutes after it was detected on NATO radar screens, they said.
   Lt. Col. Michael R. Gannon, a spokesman at Supreme Headquarters
Allied Powers Europe near Casteau, Belgium, said NATO officials had
hoped the MiG would head out over the North Sea, where the F-15s
could shoot it down safely.
   Another official at the headquarters said privately the decision
was made not to attack over land because, ``when it is shot in the
air at high altitude, you don't know where it is going.''
   MiG-23s can fly at supersonic speeds and, within the Warsaw Pact,
are used only by the Soviet and East German air forces. The
aircraft, known in the West by its NATO code name Flogger, was first
shown in public at a Moscow air show July 9, 1967.
   Twelve versions of the MiG23 have been produced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890704-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissidents     07-04 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissidents,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Protest Leaders Say Movement Will Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two leaders of China's pro-democracy movement
said in a statement from hiding Tuesday that they had formed a
coalition to reignite the fight for a freer China.
   Student leader Wu'er Kaixi and top intellectual dissident Yan
Jiaqi said the new organization would unite forces advocating
political change in China.
   ``The movement for democracy has flooded its banks like the
Yellow River,'' they said. ``It is unstoppable.
   ``Despite the unprecedented white terror, the Chinese student
movement and the movement for democracy are still alive. At present,
China is shrouded in silence, but that just means that a new and
bigger storm is brewing.''
   The Associated Press obtained a copy of the statement from Hong
Kong activists who helped smuggle the two dissidents out of China
last month. A videotape of Wu'er reading the statement and Yan
adding brief comments was shown on television in Hong Kong and
France, where the two are believed hiding.
   They said donations would fund what they referred to as a
``united committee for democratic movements,'' and they called on
``people who love freedom around the world'' to provide support.
   Students in China and Chinese living in foreign countries have
established dozens of organizations to promote democracy, causing
internal splits in the movement. Activists have said they hope Yan
and Wu'er can put an end to these feuds.
   ``The 1989 democracy movements is the most glorious page in
Chinese modern history,'' the statement said. ``The ideals of the
movement have shown the world that Chinese democracy will never
die.''
   ``We refuse to adopt terrorist methods under any conditions,''
the statement said, adding that Chinese revolutionary leader Mao
Tse-tung's adage that political power grows out of the barrel of a
gun ``cannot lead China to true freedom, liberty and democracy.''
   The dissidents proposed that the citizens killed during the June
3-4 military crackdown in Beijing's Tiananmen Square be awarded the
Nobel Peace Prize. One student leader, Chai Ling, of Beijing Normal
University, has already been nominated by two members of the
Norweigian Parliament. Her whereabouts is unknown.
   The statement called on all Chinese to set aside Sept. 12, 100
days from the crackdown, as a day of remembrance for those who died.
It also set June 4 as a day of national mourning for China.
   Wu'er and Yan led two pro-democracy organizations, one for
students and the other for intellectuals. Chinese authorities
declared both organizations illegal, and the two are among China's
most wanted fugitives.
   The two men said they met with other dissidents from June 27 to
Monday to discuss the new organization. They did not say where the
meetings took place.
   ``The meeting unanimously decided that the June 4 massacre is not
the end of the 1989 Chinese democratic movement but rather it is the
beginning of a new consciousness of democracy in China,'' they said.
   The pair predicted the quick downfall of senior leader Deng
Xiaoping, Premier Li Peng and President Yang Shangkun, the group of
hard-liners who ordered the crackdown.
   ``It won't take too long for a larger student movement and
movement for democracy to once again arise in China,'' they said.
``A reactionary regime that can only be maintained by tanks and
machine guns certainly will be smashed by this storm.''
   They said the assault on Tiananmen Square ``was not just a crime
against China's students and people, but also a challenge against
the basic principles of life and all humanity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
