<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FatFish     07-04 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fat Fish,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gluttonous Grouper Celebrates Truly Independent Fourth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gluttonous grouper who ate his
high-priced tankmates at a pet shop had his first full day of
freedom in 18 months on Independence Day.
   A year and a half after being snatched from the Florida Keys, the
3{-foot, 35-pound fish was returned to the ocean with a net one mile
offshore Monday.
   Wearing scuba gear, Terry Haley patted his pet one last time.
Then Flazey _ short for fat and lazy _ meandered toward the ocean
floor 140 feet down.
   ``It was nice of him to hang around for a while,'' Haley said.
   Flazey made headlines in May when he ate tankmates worth $5,000
at an aquarium store in Lansing, Ill. Haley, the store owner,
complained that Flazey was eating up the profits.
   ``It'd be great to know where he is right now,'' Haley said after
giving Flazey his freedom. ``He's probably looking at the menu.''
   At the store, Haley fed the grouper 5 pounds of smelt every other
day. Flazey, however, snacked on expensive fish and tried to wolf
down a 2-foot nurse shark. In the end, Haley decided to return the
grouper to his natural home.
   Flazey, a brown spotted jewfish, a member of the grouper family,
was a foot long and weighed 3 pounds when he was caught.
</TEXT>
