<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines Pvs; CORRECTS day to TUESDAY in lede.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan was hospitalized
in Arizona on Tuesday with an injury suffered while hunting in
Mexico, the Secret Service said.
   ``We understand he was on a horse in Sonora and apparently he was
injured,'' said Agent Allan Cramer, spokesman for the service.
   Reagan, 78, was taken to the base hospital at Fort Huachuca, near
Tucson, Cramer said.
   Sonora is a Mexican state just across the Arizona border.
   Cramer said his information came from agents with the former
president's protective detail. He did not know the nature of
Reagan's injury.
   In Kennebunkport, Maine, White House staff members vacationing
with President Bush said they had been informed Reagan suffered no
broken bones and was hospitalized simply for observation.
   ``There was a riding accident of some sort,'' said a senior White
House official who asked not to be identified.
   Bush was boating ``will be informed just as soon as he gets in.''
