<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Abortion-Reaction     07-04 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Reaction,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Group Says U.S. Ruling Affects Women Everywhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The London-based International Planned Parenthood
Federation said Tuesday the U.S. Supreme Court's decision on
abortions will harm women around the world, but the Vatican said it
did not go far enough.
   ``When America sneezes, the rest of the world catches
pneumonia,'' said Dr. Halfdan Mahler, secretary-general of the
federation, which has member groups in 128 countries.
   He said the court's Monday ruling was ``out of step with recent
international trends, which have tended to recognize new grounds of
justification for abortion.''
   The court, while not reversing its 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision
legalizing abortion, in a 5-4 ruling made it possible for state
governments to impose restraints and withhold funding for abortions.
   In a statement, Mahler said the ruling was ``bound to worsen the
plight of the millions of women around the world who annually die or
are permanently impaired from unwanted pregnancies, or from illegal
abortions.''
   The federation estimates that 30 million to 55 million induced
abortions occur worldwide annually, and perhaps half are performed
by unskilled people, mainly in the developing world, ``mostly in
settings where abortion is legally restricted.''
   But the Vatican newspaper said Tuesday the decision did not go
far enough because it did not outlaw abortion.
   ``The problem of the suppression of conceived life remains,''
headlined L'Osservatore Romano in a commentary on Monday's ruling.
   The article pointed to the ``importance and value'' of the
ruling, saying the decision ``rectified'' the 1973 ruling that a
woman's decision to have an abortion during the first three months
of pregnancy must be left to her and her doctor.
   In Canada, Justice Minister Doug Lewis said the U.S. Supreme
Court ruling mirrors what has quietly happened in Canada.
   ``If anything, this decision highlights what I have felt has been
a shift in the focus in Canada that hasn't really been noticed
yet,'' Lewis said. ``I think in Canada we are seeing a shift in the
importance of the issue from the federal level to the provincial
level.''
   In an editorial, The Times of London said: ``Yesterday's Supreme
Court decision... has ensured that the most divisive issue in U.S.
politics will also be the most dominant.
   ``In future, most educated, middle-class women will be able to
command an abortion just as they do now, by paying for private
treatment, by moving from restrictive states to free ones, or both.
The poor and the uneducated will find it harder, perhaps
impossible.''
</TEXT>
