<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Legislature     07-04 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislature Rejects Economics Nominee a Second Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Soviet voted Vladimir M. Kamentsev down
Tuesday in his second try for approval as director of foreign
economic policy, even though the rules were made easier after his
first rejection last week.
   Kamentsev, 61, was criticized for ``thoughtlessly permitting the
sale of raw materials and other national assets,'' said Tass, the
official news agency. He has been chairman of the Foreign Economic
Commission for 2{ years.
   Tass said the vote was 200 votes for Kamentsev, 172 against and
47 abstentions, short of the majority necessary for approval.
   Since the Supreme Soviet convened June 26, replacing the old
rubber-stamp parliament of the same name, members have questioned
most Cabinet nominees and criticized many.
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov withdrew the names of seven nominees
after unfavorable committee hearings.
   Ryzhkov told the Supreme Soviet on Tuesday he would offer another
candidate, but said he still thought highly of Kamentsev, Tass
reported.
   By the rules in effect Friday for the first vote, Kamentsev
needed the support of a majority of all 542 members of the Supreme
Soviet but got the votes of only 246.
   The rules were changed this week so a nominee needs only a
majority of the members voting, but Kamentsev still lost.
   According to the Tass report, several deputies questioned his
competence and his ability to make radical changes in foreign
economic policy. Kamentsev has been criticized for problems in
foreign trade during his tenure, and Tass said several deputies
accused him of lacking a coherent program.
   His commission was created in January 1987 as part of a
reorganization of foreign trade agencies under President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's economic reform program.
   Gorbachev has put increased emphasis on foreign trade in his
efforts to reform an economy plagued by shortages and poor quality
of consumer goods.
   Heated debate accompanied Nikolai A. Pugin's nomination to
continue as minister of automotive and agricultural machine
production, but he was confirmed.
   Tass said legislators accused the ministry of failing to produce
quality equipment for agriculture, one of the weakest sectors of the
Soviet economy. Pugin proposed ending the monopoly of major plants
producing agricultural machinery, and expanding and updating
production.
   The Supreme Soviet approved incumbent Konstantin Katushev as
minister of foreign economic relations with only 37 negative votes,
Tass said, and confirmed Ivan S. Silayev as deputy premier for
machine building, Apollon S. Systsov as aircraft industry minister
and Vitaly F. Konovalov as nuclear power minister.
</TEXT>
