<DOCNO> AP890704-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ecuador     07-04 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecuador,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Coalition Ends, Minister Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ecuador's ruling coalition formally split
and the minister for industry resigned in a political crisis sparked
by growing economic instability, officials said Tuesday.
   The Popular Democracy Party announced Monday it was withdrawing
its support from the government led by President Rodrigo Borja, who
took office in August.
   The party had signed an alliance with Borja's Democratic Left
Party when Borja took office, giving the ruling coalition a majority
in Congress.
   ``I resigned according to the resolution of my party,'' Juan Jose
Pons, the minister for industry and commerce said Tuesday. A second
Popular Democracy official, Juan Pablo Moncagatta, president of the
Housing Board, also resigned.
   Vladimiro Alvarez, who was chosen to lead the Popular Democracy
Party in May, had said the alliance with Borja's government damaged
the party's image. Ecuador, an oil-producing OPEC member nation, is
confronting its first severe economic crisis in two decades.
Inflation is at an annual rate of 84 percent.
   Alvarez said, however, his party will continue to support
government legislation before Congress. The Popular Democracy party
has seven congressmen, while the Democratic Left has 30, meaning
together they have a majority in the 71-member legislative body.
   Petroleum financed an economic boom that propelled a near-feudal
society into the 20th century in just two decades, created a
prosperous middle class and eased social tensions. But estimates are
that by the turn of the century the oil that brought affluence to a
poor nation will have run out.
   But even before the oil runs out, Ecuador is experiencing hard
times. Oil exports currently account for 50 percent of the nation's
income, down from 75 percent in the early 1980s. Low world oil
prices in 1986 and a major earthquake a year later that temporarily
halted oil exports plunged the country into a financial crisis.
   Borja, who began a four-year term in August 1988, has attempted
to resolve the economic problems by imposing unpopular austerity
measures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
