<DOCNO> AP890704-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Economy     07-04 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Economy,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Deputies Attack Government Economic Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associatd Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting like old political pros, Solidarity
deputies heaped scorn on the government's economic performance on
Tuesday at the opening of the first Parliament with independent
opposition in 40 years.
   The discussion came after the communist government formally
submitted its resignation to the Sejm, or parliament, which now
counts 161 Solidarity deputies among its 460 members following
June's partially democratic elections.
   In his first speech as a deputy, Solidarity veteran Jacek Kuron
took on Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, who looked on from a
balcony.
   Kuron, toughened by nine years in jail for opposition activities,
told the chamber that Solidarity deputies had been tracking
government policy with ``deep concern.''
   He said the government refrained from increasing prices during
the election campaign, but let loose a huge array of price rises
once communist authorities suffered a humiliating defeat and
Solidarity scored a triumph in the June vote.
   Poles commonly refer to their economy as a catastrophe. Consumers
face an inflation rate of 100 percent. Price increases in the last
two weeks raised the cost of sugar, cigarettes, alcohol, gasoline,
refrigerators and washing machines.
   The value of the dollar, Poland's most valued currency,
fluctuated wildly last week due to uncertainty over further price
rises. The rate stabilized after the government announced a
monthlong price and wage freeze as of July 1.
   Not resolved yet is whether Solidarity will enter a government
and take part of the responsiblity for seeking a way out of the
economic crisis.
   Kuron attacked the government for announcing increases not agreed
upon with trade unions and for failing to provide safeguards for
people on pensions and fixed incomes. ``Such a chaotic policy caused
only social unrest,'' he said.
   Deputy Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula defended government policy.
He said government expenditures were running ahead of revenue and so
prices were raised on cigarettes and alcohol, since the government
earns tax revenue on those items.
   Solidarity deputy Ryszard Bugaj, a specialist on economic
affairs, found Sekula's explanation ``unacceptable.''
   Another Solidarity deputy, Ryszard Brzuzy of Belchatow, where a
large power plant was hit by a strike this year, called on the
government to present a detailed report on its activities before
resigning.
   The faltering economy is emerging as a major issue. Bad
investments based on Western credits have burdened Poland with a $38
billion foreign debt.
   Poles themselves keep at home billions of dollars more _ earned
abroad or sent by relatives _ because they don't trust
government-run banks.
   Solidarity and official economists agree that the task of the
next government, whether formed by Solidarity or the communist
coalition, will be to build confidence among Poles and foreign
creditors.
   Solidarity has been actively pursuing foreign credits since June
for specific investment projects as well as for buying consumer
products and foodstuffs to satisfy consumer demand while reforms are
being implemented.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
