<DOCNO> AP890704-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1853EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-04 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hot From Southwest To Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures soared to record highs Tuesday on the northern
Plains, and rain dampened the Fourth of July across much of the East.
   A ridge of high pressure in the upper atmosphere helped push
temperatures upward from the Southwest to the northern Plains.
   Temperatures soared past 110 degrees in sections of the
California desert.
   Elsewhere, Fargo, N.D., hit a record 96 degrees; Jamestown, N.D.,
reached a record 97; and Williston, N.D., hit a record 100.
   In the East, thunderstorms were most numerous from the central
Gulf Coast to the Carolinas. Locally heavy rain also fell in
sections of the lower Great Lakes and mid-Atlantic Coast states.
   Heavy rain in the rugged Blue Ridge Mountains of western North
Carolina produced flash floods and hundreds of campers had to be
evacuated, with some requiring help to escape over rising streams.
   Thunderstorms produced tornadoes near the central Gulf Coast at
Gulf Shores, Ala., and about 8 miles west of Crestview, Fla., the
National Weather Service said.
   Heavier rain during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT including 1.61
inches at Charlotte, N.C.; 1.37 inches at at Fort Belvoir, Va.; and
1.26 inches at Pensacola, Fla.
   The rainfall during the past few months in the Southeast is a
reversal of a drought that affected many areas for several years. At
Jackson, Miss., the change from last year is quite sharp. Between
May 1 and July 4 last year, only 0.77 of an inch of rain fell;
during the same period this year, 16.70 inches of rain was recorded.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 116 at Palm Springs, Calif. Tuesday's
low for the Lower 48 states was 28 degrees at Truckee and South Lake
Tahoe, Calif.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Gulf Coast states to the Tennessee and Ohio
valleys and the East Coast; showers and thunderstorms over sections
of Minnesota and the Dakotas; and isolated afteroon thunderstorms
over the Rockies and eastern Arizona.
   Highs only in the 60s and 70s were predicted over the Pacific
Northwest and along the California coast; mostly in the 80s from the
Mississippi Valley to the Atlantic Coast, with some 70s in the
Appalachians and lower 90s over Florida; in the 90s to near 100
degrees from the great Plains to lower elevations of the Rocky
Mountain states and westward to the interior valleys of California;
and between 105 and 120 degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
