<FIRST>r w AM-TeacherConvention 3rdLd-Writethru a0639 07-04 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Convention, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0639,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEA Condemns School `Choice' Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``However, the...'';
picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``In another...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Education Association on Tuesday
adopted a resolution condemning state and federally mandated
``choice'' programs permitting parents to choose their children's
public schools, saying it damages quality education for all students.
   But the union is not opposing such plans if adopted by local
authorities on their own.
   The huge teachers' union, in its first policy statement on the
hot education issue, said it opposes wide requirements for such
programs and ``continues to support alternative programs in the
public schools for specific purposes.''
   The NEA also plans to establish criteria for evaluating choice
plans, according to a new-business item adopted Monday.
   Officials have said NEA supports magnet schools, alternative
schools and other options.
   The resolution approved Tuesday at the group's convention was
more stringent than several proposals on the table but less
restrictive than others in that it left a loophole for choice plans
adopted by district officials.
   Choice plans enable parents to pick their child's school.
President Bush has called the concept a cornerstone of education
reform, contending that competition will force all schools to
improve.
   However, the NEA and other groups say choice plans have the
potential to weaken and resegregate the schools left behind,
particularly plans that don't provide student transportation and
that reduce tax dollars to schools abandoned by students.
   Education Undersecretary Ted Sanders said through spokesman Tom
Lyon the vote was ``very disappointing. All students deserve access
to a quality education _ and choice will make that happen. But
apparently the NEA doesn't even understand the concept.
   ``The president and the secretary have called choice the
cornerstone for rebuilding American education. Parents want choice;
students need it _ now,'' Sanders said.
   In another development announced at the convention Tuesday,
school districts in four states will experiment with close teacher
involvement in fundamental changes.
   One example in the ``Learning Laboratories'' program: In Memphis,
Tenn., inner-city schools will be controlled by a council on which
teachers will outnumber administrators.
   In Westerly, R.I., a computer will link schools, parents and
local government.
   The other projects are in Chaska, Minn., and Marshalltown, Iowa.
   The 8,500 delegates at the NEA's Representative Assembly have
been voting on policies and resolutions since convening on Sunday.
Among those approved, the 2-million-member teacher union:
   _Will request television stations and newspapers to put the names
of states on their weather maps. This was proposed by the Montana
delegation in the interests of geographic literacy.
   _Will notify President Bush of its disappointment that he did not
accept an invitation to speak at its convention and will ask that he
meet with the group's newly elected leaders to discuss ``the future
of our nation's children.''
   _Joined many other education groups in condemning Channel One, a
TV news program with commercials that is designed for classroom use.
The group called it ``an attempt to gain control of students for
commercial purposes in exchange for free equipment'' such as VCRs
for schools.
   _Will draft a blueprint for an aggressive 1990-91 campaign to win
higher salaries for teachers. The plan is to include TV spots,
``dramatic press conferences'' and newspaper and magazine articles
``focusing on the dedication of public school employees and the need
to reward them with professional pay.''
   The union contends that reforms made without teacher input are
destined to fail. The ``Learning Laboratories'' program is designed
to promote site-based decision-making with teachers as major players.
   To qualify as Learning Labs, NEA affiliates in each of the
participating districts have had to demonstrate that their local
school board and superintendent are committed to district-wide
change.
   The initial Learning Lab experiments are expected to last at
least five years each. The NEA has set aside $280,000 for the
project this year; the money will go for technical support and
$5,000 grants to each district. The districts are in:
   _Memphis, which is closing inner-city schools and reopening them
as democratically controlled school communities each governed by a
council of three teachers, two administrators, two parents and one
local resident.
   _Chaska, Minn., which has created a review panel that gives
grants to teachers for innovative approaches to learning _ including
one experiment in which three teachers have been elected to be
principals of their elementary schools while continuing to teach.
   _Marshalltown, Iowa, which is eliminating central office
decision-making on instruction and designating teachers to create
teacher teams responsible for decisions on key curriculum and
resource issues.
   _Westerly, R.I., which is using computers to link schools to
parents, the town government and educational resources in the school
district.
   The union also passed a resolution saying that it is ``deeply
concerned'' about Boston University's takeover of the Chelsea,
Mass., school system and said state and local governments should
provide the help needed to deal with systems like Chelsea's.
   The union also approved a series of recommendations to the
National Board for Professional Teaching Standards, a panel which is
developing standards for voluntary teacher certification.
   Among other things, NEA is demanding that the board not seek a
link between certification and compensation, and offer only one kind
of certificate.
</TEXT>
