<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-CabinetChase     07-04 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Cabinet Chase,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Cabinet Minister Hurt During Police Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal Cabinet minister driving a motorcycle in
zig-zag fashion early Tuesday suffered a concussion when he crashed
while being pursued by a police car, police reported.
   They said Consumer and Corporate Affairs Minister Bernard
Valcourt, 37, an avid biker who likes to wear black leather and tour
his native New Brunswick province on his 1,000-cubic centimeter
Yamaha, hit a curb and piled head first into a wooden fence.
   ``His life at the moment is not in danger,'' Dr. Jacques
Francoeur, the neurosurgeon treating Valcourt at l'Enfant-Jesus
Hospital in Quebec, said.
   Delbert Pelletier, deputy police chief of Edmunton, said Valcourt
was driving his motorcycle there when police tried to pull him over.
   ``The police cruiser was ordered to check the driver of the
motorcycle moving from side to side across the lane,'' Pelletier
said.
   ``When the cruiser turned on its lights, he accelerated away from
them, turned onto a boulevard and lost control.''
   Francoeur said Valcourt lost consciousness on impact and suffered
a slight to moderate concussion and broken facial bones. He had to
be heavily sedated during the trip to Quebec aboard a Quebec
government plane equipped with ambulance services.
   But he told reporters that Valcourt, father of two girls, was
able to squeeze doctors' hands when asked to do so shortly after
being admitted to hospital at about 6.30 a.m.
   ``Tests indicate that there is no particular damage to the
brain,'' the doctor said.
   ``He's under medical observation and there should be a definite
improvement in 24 to 48 hours.''
   L'Enfant-Jesus handles major neurological cases from northwestern
New Brunswick.
   Valcourt, a lawyer and a native of St. Quentin, near Edmundston,
was elected to the House of Commons in 1984 in the
Madawaska-Victoria constituency and kept the seat after a tight race
in last November's election.
   He was a parliamentary secretary and minister of state for small
business and tourism before being named consumer and corporate
affairs minister in January.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney described Valcourt as ``one of the
most impressive young politicians I've ever run into'' upon being
informed of the accident. ``He's someone for whom I have great hopes
for the future.''
</TEXT>
