<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AmericanHomecoming 1stLd-Writethru a0636 07-04 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Homecoming, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independence Day Lives up to Its Name For Exiled American</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Stolar arriving, quotes,
color; picks up 6th graf, `Stolar, whose ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independence Day lived up to its name for Abe
Stolar, who made an emotional return to his hometown for the first
time since his family emigrated to the Sovet Union nearly 60 years
ago.
   ``I really can't find words,'' the 77-year-old Stolar told a
crowd of well-wishers and reporters as he stepped off a flight
Tuesday evening at O'Hare International Airport.
   Stolar was traveling from Israel, where he emigrated earlier this
year after a long fight to leave the Soviet Union.
   He said he had longed to return to the city he and his family
left for the Soviet Union when he was a teen-ager, but feared it
might never happen.
   ``I was an alien there for all the 58 years I was there,'' said
the native Chicagoan. ``It was a crime they didn't let me out.''
   He plans to get reacquainted with the city of his birth and to
tour the nation, taking in some baseball, junk food and other
all-American fare.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., who helped secure Stolar's release from
the Soviet Union, was on hand for the welcome home. He presented
Stolar and his Soviet-born wife, Gita Rozovskaya, a bouquet of red
roses, an American flag and a T-shirt reading, ``Chicago.''
   The senator called Stolar ``a real hero, a guy who has stood up
for freedom.''
   ``It is fitting Abe should return home to Chicago on the Fourth
of July,'' Simon said.
   Stolar, overwhelmed with emotion, searched for words to express
his feelings.
   ``What can I say, really,'' he said. ``I can't say anything but
thank you, thank you, thank you!''
   Stolar, whose parents immigrated from Russia in 1910, was raised
on the Northwest Side. But when he was 19, in 1931, the family
returned to their homeland, believing the Bolshevik Revolution had
created a workers' paradise.
   It didn't turn out that way.
   Stolar's father died in the Stalinist purges, and his mother and
sister were sent to camps in Siberia. Stolar was wounded by a German
hand grenade and lost the sight in one eye.
   He served in the Red Army during World War II, then worked as a
translator and announcer for Radio Moscow. But after nearly five
decades in the Soviet Union, Stolar wanted out.
   His exit proved more difficult than his entry.
   Promises that he could leave were repeatedly broken by Soviet
officials, who refused to let the whole family leave the country.
   After a 14-year fight, Stolar finally won freedom. In March, he,
his wife, son, daughter-in-law and two grandchildren headed for
Israel, where they now live.
   ``We feel pampered by fate after all those disgusting, wasted,
stupid years,'' Stolar wrote in a recent letter to Simon. ``As so
many people have said before me, what a pity it comes so late in
life.''
   On visiting Chicago, he wrote, ``It will be a look at the old
town, which will really be all new to me, that few visitors, though
native born, can enjoy.''
   His agenda includes a baseball game at Wrigley Field, which looks
pretty much the same except for the new lights that will allow him
to catch Wednesday's night game between the Cubs and the San Diego
Padres.
   Stolar dreamed of one day staying in the fancy, 3,000-room
Stevens Hotel, a dream that will come true.
   The hotel, now the Chicago Hilton and Towers, has offered the
Stolars its 23rd-floor Chicago Suite. Despite recent refurbishing,
the grand ballroom and grand salon, glittering with mirrors and gold
leaf, are virtually unchanged, said assistant manager Peter Borup.
   No special menu is planned during Stolar's weeklong stay; he's
``a junk-food junkie'' who likes hamburgers and hot dogs, Borup said.
   Other stops on the Stolars' 12-city U.S. tour include Anchorage,
Alaska, and Miami. They'll end the trip with an Aug. 13 visit to Los
Angeles.
   Their visit was arranged and financed by Chicago Action for
Soviet Jewry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
