<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Bush     07-04 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Bush,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Invites Hungarians To Meet Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarians who received coveted
invitations to a Fourth of July reception given by U.S. Ambassador
Mark Palmer got a second invitation on Tuesday _ to greet President
Bush next week.
   As the guests left, they were handed scrolls that contained a
typewritten sheet proclaiming in English and Hungarian that
``Everyone is invited'' to turn out to cheer for Bush when he
arrives on July 11 on the first visit by an incumbent U.S. president
to this communist-ruled nation.
   ``President Bush looks forward to greeting the people assembled
on Kossuth Square,'' it said, noting that this is his ``only
appearance in Hungary before the general public.''
   Kossuth Square is named after Lajos Kossuth, leader of Hungary's
ill-fated 1848 revolt against its Austrian rulers. It lies adjacent
to Budapest's historic parliament building.
   U.S. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, have
indicated they see Bush's East European swing as a counterpoint to
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's successful trips to the
West, where he has often been greeted by enthusiastic crowds.
   At least some of Bush's visit will be broadcast live on Hungarian
television and radio.
</TEXT>
