<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Extremists     07-04 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Extremists,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Membership In Right-Wing Extremist Groups Climbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Minister Wolfgang Schaeuble
said Tuesday that membership in right-wing extremist groups climbed
a dramatic 12.8 percent last year and continues to rise.
   He also expressed concern about the increasingly popular
ultrarightist Republican Party headed by former Nazi SS soldier
Franz Schoenhuber. Schaeuble said many Republican pronouncements
``are similar to speech used by representatives of extremism.''
   Schoenhuber says his party is not extremist, but speaks out for
German interests and supports constitutional law.
   Membership in organizations officially labeled ``right-wing
extremist,'' including neo-Nazi groups, climbed to 28,300 last year
from 25,200 the year before, Schaeuble said. Those figures do not
include the estimated 13,000 Republicans, whose party has not been
officially labeled ``right-wing extremist.''
   Schaeuble said membership in right-wing extremist groups
continues to grow in this nation of 61 million, and may have already
surpassed 30,000.
   The Republicans concentrate on nationalist themes. They advocate
radical reductions in the number of asylum-seekers allowed to stay
in West Germany and strict limits on foreign workers.
   The party has made strong election showings in the past six
months, including winning its first seats in the European Parliament.
   Schaeuble told reporters that state and federal officials will
meet in September to examine whether the Republicans should be
labeled a right-wing extremist organization. If that happened, the
party would be kept under surveillance by the Verfassungschutz, the
country's main domestic intelligence agency.
</TEXT>
