<FIRST>u a AM-UMWRally 1stLd-Writethru a0624 07-04 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW Rally, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cesar Chavez Addresses UMW Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with rally, speeches by Chavez,
UMW vice president, comment by Pittston president; picks up 7th graf pvs,
`If we lose ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Farm Workers President Cesar Chavez
told more than 5,000 striking United Mine Workers and supporters who
rallied on the Fourth of July that their fight was just ``and people
never lose a just fight.''
   Chavez told the miners they faced economic tyranny from Pittston
Coal Group Inc. similar to the tyranny faced by American colonists
under King George III that led to the Declaration of Independence
213 years ago.
   ``The best place to spend the Fourth of July is here because the
struggle for freedom continues,'' Chavez, speaking from a flatbed
truck, told the gathering in a muddy field in the heart of the
southwest Virginia coalfields.
   ``We come from the battlefields of California to the battleground
of these coalfields,'' said Chavez. He urged strikers to continue
employing non-violent tactics of civil disobedience and asked the
crowd to join his union's boycott of grapes.
   ``Your struggle is our struggle. This is a just fight and people
never lose a just fight,'' he said.
   During the rally, UMW Vice President Cecil Roberts said the
National Labor Relations Board has declared the strike to be over
unfair labor practices committed by Pittston, rather than over
economic matters, such as wages and benefits.
   Roberts said the ruling by the board's general counsel means
striking miners will get their jobs back when a contract is
eventually signed.
   The determination brings additional pressure on Pittston to
resume contract negotiations, Roberts said. Talks broke off last
month and Pittston declared negotiations at an impasse.
   Pittston President Michael Odom said company officials will meet
with NLRB representatives to review the allegations of unfair labor
practices, and may fight the ruling before an administrative law
judge.
   ``Our position is that the board is in error,'' Odom said. ``This
is clearly an economic strike, one over terms and conditions of the
contract.''
   Odom said the NLRB ruling will have no effect on negotiations.
   The strike by 1,900 UMW members against Pittston Coal Group
operations in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky has spawned
sympathy strikes that have idled some 37,000 workers in several
coal-mining states.
   At least a thousand of those wildcat strikers attended the rally.
   Dan Emmons of Booneville, Ind., who walked off his job at a
Peabody Coal Co. mine, said earlier that all UMW members have a
stake in the strike against Pittston, which is trying to break away
from an industry-wide contract with the union and win concessions.
   ``If we lose here, it's just going to be a chain reaction jumping
from company to company,'' he said.
   ``These boys need help down here,'' said Emmons. ``The main thing
we can do is keep their morale up and let them know they're not
standing alone.''
   Miners said the wildcat strikes, which began June 12 and are
officially unauthorized by the union, would continue until a
contract is signed.
   ``They'll last until this is settled,'' said Larry Heck of
Booneville, also a Peabody employee.
   Roger Myers, a UMW executive board member for Indiana, said about
125 cars, each carrying three or four Hoosier mine workers, left
southern Indiana on Sunday to attend the rally.
   Since the wildcat strikes began 2{ weeks ago, more than half of
Indiana's 1,750 striking coal workers have traveled to Virginia in
three separate caravans to show their support, Myers said.
   ``Those trips have made their resolve just that much stronger,''
Myers said.
   ``They go down there and break bread, so to speak, with the
strikers. It's just been unbelievable the way it's buoyed everyone's
spirits,'' he said.
   ``Every union man should be there,'' said Buster Varney, a strike
captain for UMW Local 5737 in Stone, Ky.
   Court orders have curtailed the union's strike activities around
Pittston mines and processing plants, so the UMW has turned to
rallies as an outlet for the idled miners. Tuesday's rally was the
third in the heart of the southwestern Virginia coal fields in three
weeks.
</TEXT>
