<DOCNO> AP890704-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 2223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ThinBlueLine     07-04 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adams Sues Producer of Film That Led To His Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man whose murder conviction was thrown out
after it was questioned in the movie ``The Thin Blue Line'' is suing
the producer of the documentary for rights to his life story.
   Randall Dale Adams' lawsuit claims producer Errol Morris lost his
rights to Adams' life story in December 1988, when he failed to
exercise a two-year option purchased from Adams for $10 in December
1986.
   Adams was convicted of murdering a Dallas police officer and
served 12 years in prison before an appeals court overturned the
conviction. The court acted after the movie was released and it
became apparent that it was unlikely Adams could have been the
triggerman. Adams was freed from prison in March, and prosecutors
declined to retry him.
   Morris said he is ``hurt and upset'' that Adams is suing him
after all he went through to get him released.
   ``I worked very, very hard for a number of years to see that
justice was done in this case and to see that Randall Adams walked
out of prison,'' Morris said recently.
   The producer said his profits from the film, which was not widely
distributed, were ``nil'' and said he is still paying off debts from
the movie.
   ``The simple thing is that when I met Randall Adams, nobody cared
about the case, no one wanted to investigate it, no one wanted to
write about it,'' Morris said.
   Adams' attorney, Randy Schaffer, said Adams, 40, is not seeking
royalties, only a declaration that he owns the right to his own life
story so he can pursue offers estimated ``in the neighborhood of six
figures.''
   ``They think they bought (Adams) lock, stock and barrel for $10,
and that's unconscionable,'' Schaffer said. ``He is grateful, but
what is he supposed to do? He's got offers to do a book and a
movie.''
   District Judge Felix Salazar on Monday postponed a hearing on the
lawsuit filed two weeks ago because the defendants filed a motion to
move the proceedings to federal court.
</TEXT>
