<HEAD>Thousands of Demonstrators Vow To Keep Abortion Legal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with rallies, flag-burnings in Atlanta,
Minneapolis, picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Massachusetts Lt....'; ADDS 5 grafs
with details.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3,000 people rallied in front of the
Statehouse in an Independence Day protest against the U.S. Supreme
Court decision giving the states broader power to restrict abortion.
   In Indianapolis, approximately 350 demonstrators, hoisting signs
and chanting ``We want free choice,'' rallied at the Indiana
Statehouse. About 400 pro-choice activists rallied outside the
Federal Building in Pittsburgh, and 350 paraded in Atlanta. In
Minneapolis, abortion rights demonstrators burning an American flag
in front of the federal building were attacked by three waiters from
a topless bar.
   Massachusetts Lt. Gov. Evelyn Murphy called for a crusade to keep
abortion safe and legal, and a coalition of abortion rights groups
followed with an announcement of a statewide campaign to vote
anti-abortion lawmakers out of office.
   ``The most fundamental liberty is the right to control our own
bodies,'' said state Rep. Susan D. Schur, a Democrat. ``For if we
have not the ability to control our own bodies, we are no more than
slaves.''
   The deeply divided court concluded its 1988-89 term by removing
some of the shackles that barred states from regulating most
abortions for 16 years. It soon could broaden state power even
further.
   Speaker after angry speaker took to the podium in Boston to
assert that no government should violate a woman's right to privacy
and no court should have jurisdiction over her body.
   ``I'm tired of those who say their moral and religious views are
universal principles,'' declared Schur. ``They then insist that
their beliefs become my law.''
   As the rally wound down, about 300 demonstrators marched down
Beacon Hill to the Esplanade along the Charles River. They demanded
the use of the microphones at the Hatch Shell to broadcast their
message to the tens of thousands of people picnicking and sunbathing
in anticipation of the annual Boston Pops concert and fireworks
display.
   About 250 police officers were already there to handle the
holiday crowds, and a line of about 30 officers prevented the
demonstrators from reaching the stage.
   ``The pro-choice outcry will be the beginning of a new American
revolution,'' Pam Nourse, head of Mass Choice, told the Beacon Hill
rally.
   Protesters waved American flags and held signs with slogans
including ``My rights have been raped.''
   In Indianapolis, speakers from women's, civil rights and abortion
rights groups told about 350 demonstrators they need to marshal
their political clout to fight anti-abortion legislation expected in
the 1990 General Assembly as a result of the Supreme Court decision.
   ``This rally marks day one in the fight for our lives,'' said
Melinda Rider, executive director of the Indiana Pro-Choice Action
League.
   ``We're going to send a message to Governor (Evan) Bayh and
legislators: `You are not going to make these decisions. We, the
people are going to make these decisions,''' said Rider.
   ``You take our rights, you lose your jobs,'' she said.
   In Pittsburgh, the 400 or so abortion rights activists were met
by as many anti-abortion activists.
   Among the youngest pickets was 3-year-old Jennette Maddok, who
held a sign that read, ``Mommy had a choice _ why can't I?''
   Her father, John Maddock, said he and his wife, Janine Maddock,
attended the abortion rights rally because ``this is a family thing
with us.''
   ``Jennette was our choice,'' Mrs. Maddock said. ``It was a
serious decision, emotionally and financially. We think it's
important for people to come out and express their opinion.''
   Marchers in Atlanta carried signs that read, ``I'm mad as hell,
and I vote'' and ``It's not Independence Day for Missouri women,''
as well as an effigy of a Supreme Court justice.
   The rally ended with the demonstrators burning the effigy with an
American flag wrapped around it. The effigy did not appear to be of
a specific justice.
   The flag-burning in Minneapolis occurred as about 150 abortion
rights demonstrators rallied outside the federal building.
   When a small group of protesters began burning a flag, three
waiters from the Solid Gold nightclub ran across the street and
attacked them, said police watch commander Ed Scott. One of the
waiters was arrested.
   Some protesters had first burned a cardboard replica of an
American flag. Sheri Smith of Action for Abortion Rights, one of the
rally organizers, said most protesters did not support the flag
burning.
</TEXT>
