<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Fourth 1stLd-Writethru   07-04 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Fourth, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0642,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Commander Says America Will Assert Rights In Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf, ``I would...' to CORRECT spelling of Cisneros.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army commander here said
Tuesday that America will keep asserting its rights in Panama and
that he hoped Panamanians someday ``will not allow a dictator to
tell them which rights they can or can not have.''
   ``I would hope that the sacrifices made by many people to obtain
our freedoms in the United States serve as an example to Latin
Americans. I hope that some day they, too, have an opportunity to
have the same basic freedoms we have,'' said Brig. Gen. Mark
Cisneros.
   ``As a Hispanic, I want to see Hispanics get the same rights we
have. Those freedoms should be basic to every country because
everybody aspires to the same freedoms that should not be demeaned
as we see here in Panama.''
   Cisneros, the target of recent attacks by Panama's
government-controlled news media, was promoted Friday from chief of
operations of the U.S. Southern Command to commander of the U.S.
Army South.
   He spoke to reporters after reviewing an Independence Day parade
of U.S. forces at Ft. Clayton.
   Cisneros dismissed accusations by Panamanian newspapers that
Washington was interfering in Panama's affairs when American troops
recently held a drill at Madden Dam, a Panama Canal installation.
   He said the drill ``was part of an exercise I ordered to defend
the canal. Under the terms of the Carter-Torrijos treaties, we have
the right to do it.''
   The dam is part of a system used to maintain the water level of
the waterway, since the Atlantic and Pacific oceans it links stand
at different levels.
   Under treaties signed in 1977 by President Jimmy Carter and Gen.
Omar Torrijos, the late Panamanian strongman, the United States has
the right to defend the canal until the year 2000, when ownership is
turned over to Panama.
   Cisneros said America faces a ``dangerous situation in Panama
with the Defense Forces'' and ``must be ready to defend (itself)
against a band of crazies.''
   The Panamanian Defense Forces are commanded by Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   Washington has tried without success to force out Noriega,
Panama's de facto leader, since he was indicted on U.S. drug
trafficking in February 1988. Noriega denies the charges.
   Cisneros dismissed accusations by Noriega that the United States
intends to invade Panama and avoid honoring the canal treaties,
calling the assertions ``part of a vicious campaign of
misinformation.''
   The United States has 12,000 troops stationed in Panama.
   Thousands of dependents and civilian employees cheered marching
units from the U.S. forces. The U.S. Embassy deputy chief of
mission, John Maisto, read an Independence Day proclamation from
President Bush.
   Most of the Americans spent the rest of the day at picnics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
