<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-04 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0829</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another sign of an economic slowdown, the
nation's purchasing managers report that the U.S. manufacturing
economy declined in June for the second straight month.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said Monday its
Purchasing Managers' Index slumped to 48.8 percent from 49.7 percent
in May. The decline put the index at its lowest level since July
1986 when it was 48 percent. The May decline was the first in 33
months.
   Production by the nation's factories was the only indicator to
increase, while new orders declined for the first time since May
1986 and inventories also fell. Vendor deliveries were faster for
the second month _ a sign of declining demand _ after 31 months in
which they were reported slower.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction fell for the fourth
straight month in May, but public building projects led overall
construction spending to a 1.3 percent increase, the government
reported.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that total private and public
construction came to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $421.3
billion in May, after falling 0.8 percent in April. May's spending
level was 3.3 percent above the pace of May 1988.
   But private construction remained flat at $335.1 billion at an
annual rate following a 1.6 percent drop in April. Residential
building was off 1.6 percent from April, including a 2.5 percent
drop in new housing units to an annual rate of $138.6 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsico Inc. snapped up two of Britain's largest
potato chip manufacturers from BSN of France in a $1.35 billion cash
deal that gives the food and beverage giant a larger share of the
European snack-food market.
   The sale, announced Monday, makes Pepsico one of the largest
snack-food producers in Europe at a time when the continent is
moving toward eliminating trade barriers by 1992.
   BSN had acquired the companies, Walkers Crisps and Smiths Crisps,
just a month ago as part of its purchase of RJR Nabisco's European
food operations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp.'s board of directors has
rejected as inadequate a $5.85 billion takeover offer from McCaw
Cellular Communications Inc. and is calling on stockholders to do
likewise, the company said.
   LIN said Monday its board concluded at a special meeting Saturday
after conferring with financial advisers Wasserstein Perella &amp; Co.
that the $120-a-share offer was not in the best interest of
shareholders.
   LIN originally decided June 19 to reject the offer and explore
other alternatives.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
in Panama has been declared ineligible for new loans from the
International Monetary Fund because it has fallen behind on
repayments of $163 million borrowed earlier.
   Panama's total debt is over $5 billion. There are 151 member
governments in the fund, including Panama. The United States has the
largest bloc of votes.
   The fund's External Relations Department announced Monday that
the ban on Panama was decided by the 22 members of the Executive
Board, who meet behind closed doors. They usually act by consensus.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's largest chemical and agro-industrial
group has announced plans to produce and market a new biodegradable
plastic made from corn starch.
   The Ferruzzi group, which controls the chemical giant Montedison,
said Monday the biodegradable plastic will be used initially to make
plastic bags, packing and napkins.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.
stepped up production here of a new four-megabit memory chip
critical to the development of the computer giant's most
sophisticated products.
   The Sindelfingen plant, about 15 miles west of Stuttgart, is only
the second plant in the world that will mass produce the complex
semiconductors for IBM. The other is in Vermont.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top public pension funds that were successful
in forcing recent changes at Exxon Corp. are urging six major oil
companies to alter their policies dealing with the environment,
safety and health issues.
   New York City and California pension funds, through their
respective trustees, delivered their message in joint letters dated
Friday to Amoco Corp., Ashland Oil Inc., Pennzoil Co., Tenneco Inc.,
Amerada Hess and Kerr-McGee Corp.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market, adrift during the long holiday weekend, posted
a modest gain Monday in the slowest trading day in more than 2{
years. The Dow Jones industrials average, down 91.81 points last
week, recovered 12.71 to 2,452.77.
   The dollar was lower against all major currencies in thin trading.
   Bonds were mixed in an abbreviated session.
   Coffee futures prices collapsed to an eight-year low as the
International Coffee Organization suspended export quotas. On other
markets, pork futures plunged, corn and soybean futures rallied
strongly and precious metals advanced.
</TEXT>
