<DOCNO> AP890704-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 0048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PensionFunds     07-04 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pension Funds,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York City, California Pension Fund Managers Urge Changes By Oil
Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of two top public pension funds, which
were successful in forcing recent changes at Exxon Corp., are urging
six major oil companies to alter their policies dealing with
environmental, safety and health issues.
   The two directors, who help manage major pension funds in New
York City and California, delivered their message in joint letters
dated June 30 to Amoco Corp., Ashland Oil Inc., Pennzoil Co.,
Tenneco Inc., Amerada Hess and Kerr-McGee Corp.
   California State Controller Gray Davis, one of the trustees for
the nation's largest public pension fund, and New York City
Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin urged the companies to add an
environmental expert to their boards of directors. They also called
for the creation of a public issues committee to monitor worker
health and safety policies, programs and practices and to recommend
changes.
   The trustees cited the March 24 oil spill involving an Exxon
tanker that dumped millions of gallons of thick crude oil into
pristine Alaskan waters as the catalyst for their latest appeal.
   ``The Exxon Valdez disaster, with its potential impact on
shareholder value, dramatizes the need for energy and chemical
companies, in particular, to aggressively promote effective
environmental and worker health and safety programs,'' the trustees
wrote.
   ``Exxon's prompt decision to meet shareholder concerns by
instituting changes in corporate policy at the board level is a
commendable response to a deplorable event.''
   California and New York joined several other pension funds after
the spill in threatening to attempt an ouster of Exxon management if
the company did not respond to the demands of shareholders
represented by the funds.
   Exxon agreed at its May shareholders meeting to present the
requests to its board.
   Davis is a member of the boards of trustees for the California
Public Employee Retirement System and California's State Teacher's
Retirement System, which hold 11.2 million shares of stock in the
six companies.
   Goldin sits on the boards of five city pension funds with more
than 2.3 million shares of stock in the companies. The funds are the
New York City Employees Retirement System, the Police Pension Fund,
the Fire Department Pension Fund, the Board of Education Retirement
System and the Teachers' Retirement System.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
