<FIRST>u f BC-BritainStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0015 07-04 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0015,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Close Higher After Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with closing share prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange rose in
dull trading Tuesday as America's Fourth of July holiday deprived
the market of trading incentives.
   Despite the lack of participation, equities gained some support
from the pound's continued strength on foreign exchange markets.
Dealers said the currency's firming trend helped ease concerns about
the outlook for British interest rates.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 8.8 points, or 0.4 percent, at 2,174.4. The index moved in a
narrow range throughout the day, showing a maximum gain of 11.2
points in early trading and a minimum gain of 6.7 points at
mid-morning.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up 8.7 points at
1800.3.
   The 500-share index finished at 1,236.04, up 4.73.
   Volume, meanwhile, sank to a meager 373.2 million shares from
Monday's 410.8 million shares.
   Dealers said they expect Wednesday also to be a day of light
trading, as a strike by public transportation workers threatens to
halt services on London's buses, subways and trains.
   The market virtually ignored news of the largest-ever monthly
fall in Britain's underlying official reserves, which indicated the
Bank of England intervened heavily to defend the pound in June.
   The Treasury reported that underlying reserves fell by the
equivalent of $2.236 billion. The previous largest fall was in April
1978, when the underlying level fell $2.115 billion.
   In major corporate news, Scottish and Newcastle Breweries made
two acquisitions in the leisure industry. The British brewer took a
65 percent stake in Netherlands-based Center Parcs for 218 million
pounds and it agreed to pay 60 million pounds for the remaining 50
percent of Pontin's Ltd. in Britain.
   Scottish and Newcastle also announced full-year pretax profit
rose 22 percent to 138.2 million pounds and said it is taking steps
to sell its Thistle Hotels unit. The brewer's share price dropped 5
pence to 332.
</TEXT>
