<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru f0014 07-04 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0014,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower in Calm European Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with late prices. Stands for AMs due
to closure of U.S. markets for the holiday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar ended slightly lower Tuesday in
European trading becalmed by the absence of U.S. traders for a
holiday and the retreat of European players to the sidelines.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Foreign exchange dealers said activity was generally light
because of the U.S. Independence Day holiday. Trading grew
progressively quieter during the afternoon.
   They attributed the overall downward trend of the dollar to
speculation about U.S. interest rates.
   ``The market is figuring that the United States will lower rates
to halt a slowdown in economic growth,'' said a trader at a large
Frankfurt bank.
   He predicted that if that happens, many investors are likely to
flee from dollars into pounds, attracted by an interest rate
differential which is favoring sterling-dominated assets.
   Traders said the dollar managed to firm to 141.55 yen in Europe
as the clouded outlook for Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party
continues to make the yen look vulnerable.
   The party's reputation has been hurt by the Recruit Co. scandal,
a second scandal involving Prime Minister Sousuke Uno's personal
life and its recent electoral losses.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.55 yen to close at 140.95 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 141.55 yen.
   Other late dollar rates compared with late Monday included 1.9220
West German marks, down from 1.9285; 1.6527 Swiss francs, down from
1.65375; 6.5375 French francs, down from 6.5485; 2.1710 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1775; 1,393.50 Italian lire, down from
1,400.50; and 1.1935 Canadian dollars, down from 1.19455.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5870 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5775 late Monday.
   Gold traded in London at a late bid price of $376.50 a troy
ounce, up from late Monday's $375.05.
   In Zurich, the late bid price was also $376.50, up from $374.35
late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.38 to close at a bid $378.31.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.24 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $5.20.
</TEXT>
