<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1455EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BugVacuum     07-04 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bug Vacuum,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Entry in The Vacuum War on Bugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The idea of sucking bugs off crops instead
of spraying them with toxic pesticides is causing a proliferation of
product names playing on the word ``vac,'' as in vacuum.
   It all started last year when Driscoll Strawberry Associates Inc.
of Watsonville designed a machine called a BugVac that uses just
enough suction to remove lygus bugs from the top parts of berry
plants while not disturbing beneficial bugs that congregate farther
down the plant.
   That idea helped spur Salinas-based Tanimura &amp; Antle Inc., the
nation's second-largest lettuce grower, to develop a machine called
Salad-Vac to vacuum bad bugs off lettuce.
   Now comes VAC-US, designed by two men from Delano, 125 miles
north of Los Angeles, for use on grapes and cotton.
   The device consists of a specially designed, five-horsepower
hydraulic fan that collects bugs in wire mesh bags after sucking
them off plants, said Harold Nelson, who designed VAC-US with Don
Neumann, his partner in Daco Farm Supply.
   The 50-pound vacuum units can be mounted in several
configurations on farm equipment to accommodate individual
requirements of farmers, Nelson said.
   He and Neumann have begun field tests of a six-unit,
tractor-mounted implement with three units on each side
hydraulically positioned around a row of grapevines. They think it
could be profitable because the cost of about $20,000 for an
eight-unit VAC-US would be considerably less than that of other
types developed so far.
   A VAC-US unit on top of the vines and one on each side can remove
up to half the flying insects on the plants as the tractor moves
between rows, Nelson said.
   Even though it doesn't eradicate all flying pests in a single
pass, Nelson thinks VAC-US will be valuable as another tool to let
growers rely less on pesticides.
   ``We're not a replacement for chemicals,'' he said. ``We're a
tool to help reduce the amount of chemicals needed. People are
looking at how to reduce pesticides, and this is another concept.''
   However, Nelson thinks repeated vacuumings will remove most
flying insects, and the number of times a grower would need to
vacuum plants depends on a particular insect's life cycle. He
estimated that a single application of pesticides would cost about
as much as three sweeps of a field with VAC-US.
   The device can be used to remove leafhoppers, white flies, moths,
weevils, thrips and lygus bugs from strawberries, grapes and cotton,
he said.
   After flying insects are sucked off the plants, beneficial
predator insects can be introduced to eliminate mites and other
bugs, Nelson said. The wire mesh bags are designed with openings
large enough to allow some surviving predators to escape.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890704-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SecuritiesIndustry Bjt   07-04 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Securities Industry, Bjt,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underwriting Revenue Plunges In First Half Of Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The amount of revenue Wall Street firms raised by
underwriting new issues of stock and bonds plunged sharply in the
first half of the year, increasing the financial pressure on
brokerage houses that are still reeling from the 1987 stock market
crash.
   Fees from bringing new stock and bond issues to the market in the
first half dropped 32 percent despite a drop of only about 3 percent
in the volume of these securities, according to Securities Data Co.,
which tracks the performance of Wall Street companies.
   The disparity is due to a 45 percent decline in the volume of
stocks issued; stock issues are much more lucrative for investment
firms than debt issues.
   Total fees charged by investment firms in the first half totaled
$1.38 billion, down from $2.04 billion in the same period of 1988,
Securities Data said.
   The volume of all securities underwritten dropped to $141.6
billion from $145.7 billion in the first half of last year.
   At the same time, the volume of straight-debt issues brought to
market increased to $72 billion, its highest level for the period in
three years. Straight debt excludes mortgage-backed securities and
other debt issues backed by assets.
   Securities Data attributed the growth in debt issues to declining
interest rates and a strong dollar, which made these investments
more attractive.
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc. was the leader in all new domestic stock
and bond issues in the first half, underwriting $25.2 billion, the
investment-house research firm said.
   Merrill Lynch raised about 91 percent of this amount through debt
offerings, making it the leading debt underwriter as well.
   In second place overall was Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., which managed
$16.9 billion in new stock and bond issues. First Boston Corp. was a
close third, at $16.3 billion.
   Despite Merrill Lynch's lead, its underwriting fees dropped 33
percent, to $194.4 million from $289.4 million in the first half of
1988. This is due to the fact that most of its underwritings were
debt issues.
   Drexel Burnham Lambert took first place in underwriting fees, at
$256.8 million. Drexel's fees were boosted by the record $149.6
million it earned in helping finance the record leveraged buyout of
RJR Nabisco Inc. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., a New York
investment firm.
   Boosted by the RJR financing, Drexel ranked first in the
underwriting of junk bonds, or high-yield debt issues, at $6.8
billion out of a total of $14.8 billion issued by all Wall Street
firms. Of Drexel's $6.8 billion, $4 billion was raised for the RJR
deal.
   Merger activity lagged in the first half compared with the first
half of 1988. Announced acquisitions of U.S. targets, valued at $10
million or greater, totaled 695, down from 784 during 1988's first
half. The total value of these planned acquisitions dropped by more
than 20 percent to $164.9 billion from $209.5 billion in the 1988
period.
   Also during the first half, initial public stock offerings
plummeted to $6.1 billion from $12.9 billion in the year-ago period
as the number of companies going public declined to its lowest level
since the second half of 1982, Securities Data said.
   In the first half, only 100 companies registered new stock
offerings compared with 138 in the first half of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890704-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Brazil-Nahas     07-04 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Nahas,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assets of Brazilian Investor Ordered Sold to Pay American Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assets of multimillionaire
businessman whose debts led to a recent stock market scandal must be
sold at auction, a judge ruled.
   The investor, Naji Nahas, owes $6.7 million to a U.S. trading
firm. The debt by the Lebanese-born Brazilian citizen forced the
closure of six brokerages and the resignation of the government's
top banker last month.
   Sao Paulo Federal District Court Judge Luis Gomes da Silva has
ordered Nahas' assets ``put on lien for future auctioning to
guarantee payment of $6.7 million'' he owes to a company identified
as Conticommodity Services Inc. of Chicago, a court clerk, who asked
not to be identified, said by phone Tuesday.
   Nahas' assets include his apartment, two properties in Sao Paulo
and shares in Selecta-Comercio e Industria, a holding company that
controls his more than 20 enterprises, the clerk said.
   The clerk said he did not know how much these assets were worth
nor when they would be auctioned.
   Nahas' lawyer, Teofilo Rocha, declined to comment when contacted
by The Associated Press.
   The O Globo newspaper of Rio de Janeiro quoted Rocha as saying he
was waiting for documents from the United States that prove Nahas
paid his debt owed to Conticommodity and that the lien on his assets
should be suspended.
   No listing for Conticommodity could be found in the Chicago
telephone book or in business directories and company officials
could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
   The U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission has linked Nahas to
Texas billionaires Nelson Bunker and William Herbert Hunt in their
unsuccessful bid to corner the world silver bullion market.
   A year ago, the Brazilian Supreme Court ratified a 1986 verdict
by a New York court that found Nahas guilty of irregularities
committed in the negotiation of 182 silver futures contracts.
   In June, Nahas was the pivot of a scandal that sent Brazilian
stock markets into a tailspin. The scandal broke June 9, when Nahas
failed to cover checks worth $31 million to pay for highly
speculative deals on the Rio de Janeiro Stock Exchange.
   On June 12, the government shut all of Brazil's stock exchanges
to avoid panic, and Nahas was prohibited from leaving the country.
The markets reopened the next day.
   Six brokerages involved in the scandal were closed and Elmo
Camoes, president of the Central Bank and owner of one of the
brokerages, resigned.
   On June 26, the federal police charged Nahas with two counts of
white-collar crime. Police said the investor in 1987 illegally tried
to take $20,000 to London and in 1983 borrowed the equivalent of $12
million from a bank of which he was a major shareholder, a violation
of Brazilian law.
   If found guilty on these two charges he could be sentenced to up
to 11 years in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
