<FIRST>r f AM-EEC-Comecon     07-04 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-Comecon,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC To Hold Final Trade Talks with Poland, Opens Talks with USSR</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community said
Tuesday it would begin talks July 7 with Poland, which should be the
last before concluding a trade and cooperation agreement.
   The EEC also said that on July 19 and 20 the EEC will hold the
first round of talks with the Soviet Union, which also are expected
to lead to a trade and cooperation agreement.
   Nico Wegter, external relations spokesman for the EEC's executive
commission, said he expected the agreement with Poland to be signed
before the commission begins its month-long summer break at the end
of July.
   The talks are a result of the mutual recognition pact signed in
June by the EEC and the Moscow-led Comecon trade bloc. Moscow's
partners in Comecon are East Germany, Poland, Czechoslovakia,
Hungary, Bulgaria, Vietnam, Cuba and Mongolia.
   Since then, the EEC has signed trade and cooperation agreements
with Czechoslovakia and Hungary and has opened negotiations with
East Germany. The only hitch so far has been the suspension of talks
with Romania, which the EEC said it would only resume if the
Bucharest government improved its human rights record.
</TEXT>
