<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 1834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Brazil-Debt     07-04 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Debt,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Delays Debt Payment But Denies New Moratorium Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil, worried about its dwindling cash
reserves, has skipped an $812 million interest payment on its debt.
But the government denied Tuesday that it plans to declare a
moratorium on foreign debt payments.
   Finance Ministry spokeswoman Rosa Alcin said in an interview that
the government had postponed the payment, due Monday, for one week
because of ``operative problems.'' She would not elaborate on the
problems.
   But, Ms. Alcin added, the delay should not be interpreted as the
first step toward a moratorium on Brazil's $112 billion foreign
debt, the largest in the developing world.
   ``A moratorium does not figure in the government's plans,'' she
said.
   Brazil owes about $9 billion to creditors in the so-called Paris
Club, composed of 10 industrialized countries with the greatest
influence in the International Monetary Fund. It was to these
nations that Monday's payment was due.
   In addition, Brazil has a $600 million payment due to private
banks later this month and $3 billion more in September.
   The delay on the current payment comes just as the Central Bank,
Brazil's equivalent of the U.S. Federal Reserve, is attempting to
stem the outflow of money from the country and keep currency
reserves from falling below a critical level.
   On Friday, the Central Bank centralized foreign monetary
operations not only for debt payments but also for export of profit,
dividends and capital by multinational companies that operate in
Brazil.
   According to Central Bank figures, $2 billion was sent abroad by
these means in the first six months, more than the $1.8 billion
transferred in all of 1988.
   At the same time, Brazil has received no new money from abroad,
although it anticipates the release of more than $4 billion promised
by the IMF, the World Bank, private banks, and the so-called
Nakasone Fund created by the Japanese government.
   The major obstacle to the release of these funds has been
Brazil's failure to reach an agreement with the IMF, which is
concerned with the government's inability to control skyrocketing
inflation.
   Inflation was 25 percent in June alone, and totaled 964 percent
in the past 12 months.
   Ms. Alcin reiterated remarks by Finance Minister Mailson da
Nobrega, who said last week that Brazil would maintain interest
payments while able to maintain an ``adequate level of reserves.''
   According to the local financial press, the government considers
the minimum level of reserves to be the equivalent $4.5 billion,
enough to purchase needed imports for three months. The last
official figures divulged showed Brazil had $5.6 billion in reserves
in June.
</TEXT>
