<FIRST>r f BC-HyundaiPlants     07-04 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hyundai Plants,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hyundai Dedicates One Plant, Announces Plans For Another</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: All dollar figures are American.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROMONT, Quebec (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyundai Auto Canada Inc. officially opened
its mammoth car assembly plant here Tuesday by announcing it will
build another plant nearby to make body parts.
   Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa, who was on hand for the opening,
said the Quebec government will grant the Korean carmaker $5.9
million (U.S.) towards the new $144.4-million parts plant. It is
scheduled to begin stamping parts such as fenders, hoods and roofs
in October 1990.
   The assembly plant, opened to the applause of about 2,000
employees and visitors, produces the Sonata mid-size sedan.
   The first Sonata rolled out Jan. 12, and Hyundai is making about
500 a week. Full production of about 2,000 cars a week or 100,000 a
year is expected to be reached in 1991, said Hyundai spokesman Greg
Young.
   The Bromont plant, about 55 miles east of Montreal, was built at
a cost of $387.7 million, with Quebec and Canadian federal
government subsidies of $131 million. It employs about 800, but that
figure is expected to grow to 1,200 once full production is reached.
</TEXT>
