<FIRST>r f BC-GeorgiaGulf-Simmons     07-04 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Georgia Gulf-Simmons,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Investor Buying Into Georgia Gulf Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of companies owned by Dallas investor
Harold Simmons has bought an 8.3 percent stake in Georgia Gulf
Corp., an Atlanta-based wholesale chemicals company.
   NL Industries Inc. of Houston and NL Chemicals Inc. of
Hightstown, N.J. acquired more than 2 million shares of Georgia Gulf
in a five-week period, paying $36.38 to $38 per share for a total of
more than $74 million, the companies said Monday in a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing.
   Georgia Gulf's stock closed Monday at $39.75, up $1.75.
   A spokesman for Georgia Gulf said it was the company's policy not
to comment on changes in stock ownership.
   Whether Simmons is making a serious play for Georgia Gulf is
unknown, said G. Bryan Dutt, an analyst who follows the company for
Howard, Weil Financial Corp. in New Orleans. ``The only one who
really knows for sure is Harold Simmons,'' Dutt said.
   Based on Simmons' past practice, he added, a takeover attempt is
likely.
   NL Industries' offices were closed Monday for the holiday, and
officials there could not be reached for comment.
   NL Industries is a holding company with most of its business
conducted through NL Chemicals, an international producer and
marketer of chemical products. Simmons is chairman of the board of
NL Industries and a director of NL Chemicals.
   Georgia Gulf, formed in 1984 through a leveraged buyout of
Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s chemical division, went public two years
later.
   Georgia Gulf supplies raw materials to other chemical firms and
to makers of plastic pipe, wood products, paints and fertilizer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
